7627, "(fr)With the destruction of the Douamoutef, we lost not only a potential new ally but also vital information on the Hammer of Light and what they are doing out here in Luyten. Hammer defections are exceedingly rare and I'm disappointed we could not capitalize on that opportunity. Flight records show it was our mistake and with more cover, the Douamoutef would have survived."
7626, "(fr)!html You did well in an uncertain situation. While we were unable to locate the ADEIS manufacturing facility, what we discovered is potentially even more strategically relevant. The sensor data gathered by the Chicxulub will be invaluable in determining the capabilities of this new installation and how the Taouret came to take advantage of it.

What we do know is that the installation does not match Terran, Vasudan, or Shivan technology, and is radically dissimilar to all known Ancient relics. We have to conclude that the artifact originates with another, previously unknown, species. Apparently, the LNA had a provisional designation set aside for such a discovery, so we're calling it the Lascaux device. While the artifact is subspace-based, its operating principles are totally unlike our own drives, or so I've been told.

While the scientists over at Amanu try to make sense of the Lascaux device, we've still got a manufacturing station to find. If anything, what we've learned about the Taouret makes it even more important that we make contact with GTA Command. Beyond that, Holly bringing in supplies through the Lascaux makes a disturbing amount of sense, and goes a long way towards explaining why they haven't seemed to have the same supply issues we have.

As for the <span class='red italic'>Douamoutef<$slashspan> and her crew, they're currently parked at the coordinates we sent. Whether they're on the level or not, the <span class='blue'>Captain<$slashspan> doesn't feel comfortable bringing a Hammer cruiser to our doorstep without precautions. We're planning a sortie with the PVN to meet and discuss terms. Infighting among HoL sects is rare, but not unheard of, and a Newet would be a valuable ally against both of our opponents. While I'm not about to start rolling out the welcome mat, we can take ally we get. Their captain hasn't taken a Terran name, and the computer suggested <span class='blue'>Captain Nakith<$slashspan>, so that's what we're going with.

Scouting operations to locate the drone hub resume in one hour."
7625, "Escadrille Alpha"
7624, "Signature Énergétique"
7623, "(fr)!html The energy signature we detected is a match for intensity, but it only lasted for a brief moment. We were expecting to find something sustained. Either way, this warrants a closer look. Alpha wing is to jump in and scout the area. We don't know what to expect out there. Get in, report what you find, and be prepared for anything. If the area is safe, we'll deploy the LNAct Chicxulub to collect detailed sensor data.

We're starting to prep reinforcements in case you need them, but we're stretched thin enough that they'll likely be our Regulus contractors. Avoid hostiles, and be extremely careful. The rest of your orders will be given on site, once we know what we're dealing with."
7622, "Vaisseau Scientifique"
7621, "(fr)!html The gurus over at Amanu put their heads together with the STX Exploration researchers and came up with a long-range search algorithm to figure out where these ADEIS drones are being made. Wayfarer and Amanu have been working with a small fleet of LNA and STX science vessels to detect and triangulate the positions of energy surges that match the search parameters. As of 30 minutes ago, we got our first hit."
7620, "Drones d'ADEIS"
7619, "Source d'ADEIS"
7618, "(fr)Pilots, let's get started.

Now that we know the true nature of our enemy, we know what to look for. The manufacturing facility would be large and fully autonomous. The energy output of such a facility should be unmistakable, and the fact that we haven't noticed such a signature on our sensors over the last few weeks is cause for concern. However, if we can find it and destroy it, then we can finally get out of this system."
7617, "(fr)!html <span class='blue'>ADEIS in Luyten<$slashspan>

If any of you think that's too noble for GTI, you'd be on to something. The ADEIS core was assembled in Antarès, specifically the Iraklion Corridor, for secrecy. Secrecy being an expensive luxury right now, the details are available in the tech room. What you need to know right now is, after the Hades' Rebellion, a fight broke out in the Iraklion over the technology. Apparently, the core activated during the fighting and fled to protect itself. Why it attacked now is currently unknown, but it's possible that the solar flare activity may have disrupted its onboard AI.

Whatever ADEIS's ultimate motives, with this new insight into our enemy, we believe we have come up with a plan to fight back. Captain Rostami will fill you in at your mission briefings. Thank you."
7616, "(fr)!html <span class='blue'>The raiders' secret history<$slashspan>

We've known for a while that the raider ships were computer controlled drones. What we didn't know was who was controlling them, or why. According to <span class='red'>Captain Varner<$slashspan> - and this has been corroborated by intel gathered at a previously hidden GTI construction facility - the drones are not controlled by anyone. At least, not anymore.

The <span class='red'>$quoteraiders$quote<$slashspan> are part of a GTI project called ADEIS, short for <span class='red'>Intersystem Entry Defense Automaton<$slashspan>. The project developed a self-sustaining drone manufacturing facility and AI controller, the latter of which is very much against interstellar law. This project began in the <span class='orange'>14 Years War<$slashspan> as a weapon to wipe the Vasudans off the map, but later transformed into a Shivan spoiler weapon. In the event that we lost that war, ADEIS would activate. Its orders were to contain the Shivan-controlled territory, gaining control of jump nodes system by system. Once containment had been achieved, it would start constructing a fleet to strike back. Like the Ancients before us, humanity would offer what aid we could to our eventual galactic successors."
7632, "Munitions pour Bombardiers"
