8222, "(fr)!html <div class='blue'>Amanu Station<br$slash>Luyten System<br$slash>2342/06/07<$slashdiv>

<span class='blue'>The hunt for IN.E.D.A.M.01<$slashspan>

I hate to be the bearer of bad news, but we've received some disturbing reports from across the system. After our engagement in the Doceitov Cloud, the IN.E.D.A.M.01 command carrier exited the Cloud and jumped to unknown regions. It's since engaged multiple LNA and STX facilities in quick succession. LNA sensor data shows that the ship is well-armed for a fire support role and deploys itself as such.

Some commanders would try to sugar-coat the situation, but I've always valued transparency. Over the last few days, IN.E.D.A.M.01 has destroyed four research and logistical outposts before deploying Marie-Morgane units to pick up the scrap. Telemetry from Wayfarer's former position suggests it takes them roughly a week to salvage everything they want. According to Captain Varner's testimony, ADEIS uses this scrap as raw materials in the construction of new drones. Based on their movements so far, we believe it will attack Amanu Station itself in two weeks plus or minus three days. Defensive strategies are being discussed. In the mean time, it is imperative that we do not do anything to provoke that ship unnecessarily.

If there's a silver lining in this situation, it's that we began system-wide evacuations early. There are only a handful of locations that still need to be evacuated. So far, ADEIS has been focused on the already-evacuated and therefore undefended sites, but at its current rate, it'll be done with them before we've evacuated everywhere that's left. Provisional patrol schedules will be distributed within the hour. If you have praxis comments, get them in quickly."
8223, "(fr)!html Pilots, an emergency is developing at the STX zero-G refinery. Ten minutes ago, IN.E.D.A.M.01 exited subspace six hours ahead of schedule and began to attack. The LNA pilots guarding the station just called for backup.

While the refinery's general function is manufacturing fuel for STX's operations, it also houses several high-pressure tanks for research into solid metal hydrogen. If ADEIS retrieved this technology, it could alleviate its need for scrap metal. Much of the refinery crew stayed aboard to scuttle all data and hardware for this research, and only began a full evacuation one hour before IN.E.D.A.M.01 arrived. Needless to say given the station's size, this wasn't enough time."
