10421, "(fr)Gamma Draconis"
10422, "(fr)The Capella / Gamma Draconis jump node is of some theoretical interest due to its unusual phasing behavior. While all jump nodes wax and wane in stability, the Gamma Draconis node exhibits an extremely long phasing period, believed to be approximately 95 years. Observation of this node has refined our measurements of several key constants in N-space physics, and the GTSc Erikson is on long-term assignment to this end. Telescopic observation of Gamma Draconis itself has revealed nothing of interest besides the star, and while current scientific models estimate that the node will become viable for travel near the end of 2351, only the discovery of another jump node would provide any reason to do so."
10423, "(fr)Uninhabited"
10424, "(fr)Epsilon Pegasi"
10425, "(fr)Epsilon Pegasi is a red giant star, and quite large even by the standard of giant stars. With four known jump nodes, Epsilon Pegasi ties with Antarès for sheer number of navigational options. After the discovery of these nodes, a series of installations were established to oversee colonization and exploration missions, eventually culminating in the construction of Enif Station, one of the first Arcadia-class installations. Due to this history, even today, more of Epsilon Pegasi's population live aboard orbital and deep-space habitats than on the system's few planets."
10426, "(fr)<br/><br/>Following Adhara's declaration of independence, Epsilon Pegasi became the site of intense conflict as elements of the GTA's Sixth Fleet defected to the new government, while loyalist elements under the GTD Delacroix tried to stop them. After a system-wide referendum, Epsilon Pegasi chose to throw in with Adhara, taking Mirfak with it."
10427, "(fr)Mirfak"
10428, "(fr)With no habitable planets, Mirfak is necessarily a small colony, and can be considered an outgrowth of the installation-building boom in Epsilon Pegasi. Given the system's unusually dense asteroid belt, many of these stations are ore processors and storage sites rather than primary habitats, and bulk carriers make up over eighty percent of the traffic through the Epsilon Pegasi/Mirfak jump node. Mirfak's economy is so closely tied to Epsilon Pegasi's that it doesn't actually have a local government, instead sharing with its neighbor. This unusual situation has left Mirfak's mining guild effectively in charge of day-to-day administration, raising some eyebrows from human rights groups.<br/><br/>Besides the node to Epsilon Pegasi, Mirfak holds a second jump node leading to an unknown system. The node is believed to have collapsed eight millennia ago, near the speculative end of the Ancient civilization discovered in Altair. One hypothesis holds that this node may lead back to Ancient space and was intentionally collapsed to slow the Shivan invasion of their territory, although there is currently no way to test this idea."
10429, "(fr)<br/><br/>When Epsilon Pegasi joined the Adhara Coalition, Mirfak was left isolated from the GTA and also joined out of necessity."
10430, "(fr)Besides the node to Epsilon Pegasi, Mirfak holds a second jump node leading to an unknown system. The node is believed to have collapsed eight millennia ago, near the speculative end of the Ancient civilization discovered in Altair. One hypothesis holds that this node may lead back to Ancient space and was intentionally collapsed to slow the Shivan invasion of their territory, although there is currently no way to test this idea."
10431, "(fr)The Adhara system is almost entirely centered on the capital planet, Annwn. A lush world with an exotic biosphere, Annwn attracted xenobiologists and wealthy tourists in equal measure. Eventually, an elaborate network of luxury habitats, scientific instruments, and weather-control stations was established to serve both populations. Being the wealthiest Frontière system in the GTA gave Adhara a unique culture, and it soon became known as a place for people seeking a fresh start. While the majority of Adhara's population live on Annwn, the system does have a small number of inhabited moons and deep-space habitats, although, in a quirk of stellar history, none of its other planets have been deemed habitable.<br/><br/>Adhara's government uses a modified parliamentary system. The legislature is divided into a number of chambers representing its commercial, ecological, and civic concerns. Alongside representatives of the colonies off of Annwn, these together form the High Parliament of Adhara. While the system does have executive and judicial branches, they are rather weak, leading the legislature to take on many functions that would normally be held by one of them$semicolon however, strict caps on the size and power any one political party is allowed to hold within Parliament serve to prevent any one group from dominating Adharan politics.<br/><br/>Adhara is nominally overseen by the GTA 10th Fleet. In practice, given the system's remote nature, 10th Fleet is little more than the flagship Malendroke and a handful of auxiliaries. While it's seen by some as a punishment detail, the reality is that the same Frontière status which made Adhara successful also make it a haven for smugglers and shady business deals, and within Adhara, the Fleet enjoys considerable prestige for its role in preventing the rampant corruption seen in other Frontière systems."
10432, "(fr)The Adhara system is almost entirely centered on the capital planet, Annwn. A lush world with an exotic biosphere, Annwn attracted xenobiologists and wealthy tourists in equal measure. As the wealthiest Frontière system in the GTA, Adhara quickly developed a unique culture, soon being known as a place for people seeking a fresh start. This was challenged by the IN.E.D.A.M.01 superweapon, which jumped to Adhara using the Lascaux network and ultimately crash-landed on Annwn's surface. The death toll of IN.E.D.A.M.01's attack was incalculable, as was its impact on the planet's biosphere$semicolon total ecological collapse was avoided only an emergency reconfiguration of the weather control satellites maintained by Annwn's tourist board. Public outcry was immediate.<br/><br/>Adhara's government uses a modified parliamentary system. The legislature is divided into a number of chambers representing its commercial, ecological, and civic concerns. Alongside representatives of the colonies off of Annwn, these together form the High Parliament of Adhara. In practice, most executive and judicial functions are also held by the legislature. With over a dozen major and minor political parties, the High Parliament tends to be highly fractious$semicolon it is highly significant, then, that the decision to declare independence following the $quoteBattle of Adhara$quote passed with over 70% of the vote.<br/><br/>Adhara's Fleet presence has historically been limited to one Orion-class warship, the GTD Malendroke, and a handful of auxiliaries, tasked with preventing the corruption seen in systems such as Regulus and Sirius from taking root in Adhara. The Malendroke's commander, Admiral Shirazi, did so through close cooperation with the Adharan people, and her promise to support Adhara's independence was likely a major factor in the decision. Adhara's fleet has since been reinforced by defectors from the GTA's 6th Fleet, with some signs of discreet logistical aid from Regulus as well."
10433, "(fr)Adhara holds a jump node to an unknown system. The node is currently too unstable for travel, but only slightly, and advances in jump drive technology may make it accessible within a Terran lifetime."
10434, "(fr)Procyon"
10435, "(fr)A binary system with a bright primary and a white dwarf companion, Procyon is on the far edge of Allied space. With only one jump node leading back to Adhara and modest natural resources, Procyon was never a high priority for colonization. It was ultimately settled by political dissidents, dissatisfied with the GTA's economic policies and intent on demonstrating the viability of a modern communist economy. Procyon has attracted some interest from economic theorists, although the decision to name their government the $quoteProcyon People's Party$quote has raised some eyebrows.<br/><br/>Procyon relies on Adhara for access to the rest of Allied space. The vastly different cultures and economic systems of both colonies give them a complex, sometimes tense relationship. At the same time, activists from Procyon are a frequent sight on Adhara's holonet, and have had some success in raising anti-central-government sentiment."
10436, "(fr) It is believed that this activism contributed to Adhara's declaration of independence. The Procyon People's Party was quick to sign on with the $quoteAdhara Coalition$quote movement, likely out of a mixture of political alignment and navigational necessity."
10437, "(fr)The Parliamentary Vasudan Empire took a different approach to colonizing space than the GTA. In the years leading up to First Contact, Vasudan explorers aggressively charted promising systems, providing detailed charts of a wide swath of space to inform later colony missions. While this strategy served them well initially, in the Antarès system, it directly lead to the Fourteen Years War. Between their initial exploration and eventual return, Terran colonists had moved in. After a series of misunderstandings lead both groups to believe the other was planning a sneak attack, Antarès became the flashpoint of a conflict that would last until the Shivan Incursion.<br/><br/>Antarès suffered greatly from its proximity to the Vasudan homeworld. Early in the war, Vasudan strategists misinterpreted surface settlements as military facilities, and on two separate occasions subjected them to orbital bombardment. Meanwhile, Antarès IV, a fuel-rich gas giant, and the Terran colony on its moon of Gulnara were the site of a prolonged battle which ended with a Terran victory, but only after the loss of thousands of lives and the failure of Gulnara's terraforming infrastructure, which sent many fleeing into underground survival shelters. The image of Antarès, a peaceful Frontière settlement ravaged by alien invaders, would become a monkey's paw for the GTA - a powerful propaganda tool that also cut short attempts at diplomacy.<br/><br/>Early in 2335, the GTA tried to finally drive the PVN from Antarès in Operation Thresher. This operation was ultimately unsuccessful, and it is speculated that the species now known as Shivans may have played a role in its failure. Shivan forces were definitively sighted in Antarès barely a week later, with their attack on the GTSc Plato being captured on video by survivors of the battle. Ironically, the GTA's anti-Vasudan propaganda may have helped save both sides: images of $quoteVasudan savagery$quote, now known to be rooted in mutual misunderstanding, inspired a generation of officers and crew just in time to fight and die against this new enemy. This was of little comfort to the people of Antarès, as both the GTA and PVN abandoned the system out of military necessity.<br/><br/>Today, Antarès is inhabited by a mixture of Terran and Vasudan war survivors. While the two groups are largely separate, the need to cooperate in the face of Shivan conquest of their system has helped cool old grudges. Among the Terran population, the political atmosphere is volatile, with arguments about reform or secession sometimes turning physical, but few believe the current system is sustainable. Common complaints include the Alliance's neglect of the system, the unavailability of modern medical care, and an exorbitant crime rate."
10438, "(fr)Allied representatives are encouraged to keep a low profile, to avoid antagonizing the locals, and above all else, to never say that the Alliance is doing the best it can."
10439, "(fr)<br/><br/>On November 26, 2336, the Antarès Federation became the ruling power in Antarès and its outlying systems."
10440, "(fr)The Parliamentary Vasudan Empire took a different approach to colonizing space than the GTA. In the years leading up to First Contact, Vasudan explorers aggressively charted promising systems, providing detailed charts of a wide swath of space to inform later colony missions. While this strategy served them well initially, in the Antarès system, it directly lead to the Fourteen Years War. Between their initial exploration and eventual return, Terran colonists had moved in. After a series of misunderstandings lead both groups to believe the other was planning a sneak attack, Antarès became the flashpoint of a conflict that would last until the Shivan Incursion.<br/><br/>Antarès suffered greatly from its proximity to the Vasudan homeworld. Early in the war, Vasudan strategists misinterpreted surface settlements as military facilities, and on two separate occasions subjected them to orbital bombardment. Meanwhile, Antarès IV, a fuel-rich gas giant, and the Terran colony on its moon of Gulnara were the site of a prolonged battle which ended with a Terran victory, but only after the loss of thousands of lives and the failure of Gulnara's terraforming infrastructure, which sent many fleeing into underground survival shelters. The image of Antarès, a peaceful Frontière settlement ravaged by alien invaders, would become a monkey's paw for the GTA - a powerful propaganda tool that also cut short attempts at diplomacy.<br/><br/>Early in 2335, the GTA tried to finally drive the PVN from Antarès in Operation Thresher. This operation was ultimately unsuccessful, and it is speculated that the species now known as Shivans may have played a role in its failure. Shivan forces were definitively sighted in Antarès barely a week later, with their attack on the GTSc Plato being captured on video by survivors of the battle. Ironically, the GTA's anti-Vasudan propaganda may have helped save both sides: images of $quoteVasudan savagery$quote, now known to be rooted in mutual misunderstanding, inspired a generation of officers and crew just in time to fight and die against this new enemy. This was of little comfort to the people of Antarès, as both the GTA and PVN abandoned the system out of military necessity.<br/><br/>After the Shivan defeat, the Hammer of Light started to move into Antarès, seeing the weakened system as a valuable staging area. While the GTA committed Admiral Po's Intrépide to contain the threat, Antarès' civilian security forces already had considerable experience against the system's pirates and smugglers and stepped up as well. Unfortunately, these two groups couldn't avoid stepping on each other's toes. A perfect storm of firebrand journalists (some with financial ties to the separatist movement), Hammer of Light military success, and a rise in criminal activity all contributed to turn public opinion in favor of independence. The nascent Antarès Federation now has exclusive access to the cluster of systems containing Ribos, Betelgeuse, and Ikeya. If its people can overcome the scars of the Terran-Vasudan War, Antarès is perfectly placed to form a new interstellar trade route."
10441, "(fr)During the Fourteen Years War, the Parliamentary Vasudan Navy presence in Bêta Cygni was something of an enigma to Terran analysts. In Antarès, the jump node to Bêta Cygni tends to shift at irregular intervals, and Vasudan raiders used it as a sally point whenever it passed near Terran positions$semicolon since the Bêta Cygni end of the node shifts in an entirely predictable pattern, the Vasudan navy was able to blockade the far side, preventing Terran forces from striking back. It was only after the war was over that the GTA learned of an entire Vasudan colony in Bêta Cygni, complete with ore processors and manufacturing centers to repair damaged warships, medical facilities for wounded soldiers, and even spiritual and entertainment centers. Bêta Cygni effectively represented a second front, one which let the PVN hide their true strength to confound GTA analysts. Sneak attacks out of Bêta Cygni have been retroactively implicated in the failure of several GTA operations in Antarès, including the infamous Operation Thresher.<br/><br/>At the end of the war, the Vasudan Navy largely left Bêta Cygni, but many of the miners and refinery workers chose to remain. A treaty between the GTA and PVE guaranteed free passage for Imperial citizens moving between Vasuda and Bêta Cygni, but these people were still relatively isolated from the Empire, and it seemed that many of them like it that way. Much like the Terran Frontière, Bêta Cygni came to provide a home for those who feel at odds with mainstream Vasudan civilization."
10442, "(fr)Parliamentary Vasudan Empire (Nominal)"
10443, "(fr)<br/><br/>After the Antarès Federation's independence was recognized, the status of the free access treaty became unclear. Federal and Imperial diplomats met with representatives of Bêta Cygni's population, and eventually agreed that everyone's best interests would be served by Bêta Cygni joining the Federation, in exchange for a favorable trade deal regarding Bêta Cygni's minerals."
10444, "(fr)A scenic 29 light-years from the Pleiades Cluster, Ribos was the first star system humanity discovered via subspace before it was identified by astronomers. The team which discovered the system named it after $quoteCaptain Ribos$quote, a superhero popular with the team lead's beloved nephew, leading to a minor outcry from the IAU; however, the excitement of a previously unknown region of space, and resultant influx of scientists, soon drowned it out. Ribos is a trinary system, with a central G-class star and two brown dwarves orbited by an extensive planetary system. Mining operations, including corona diving missions into the dwarf stars, let the scientific community in Ribos quickly set up self-sufficient settlements.<br/><br/>After first contact with the Vasudan Empire lead to the outbreak of war, Ribos shifted from a scientific outpost to a refugee station. Civilian colonists from Antarès fled the contested system, hoping that Ribos' non-military nature would protect it from PVN aggression. This worked for a time, but eventually, the GTA made the decision to base a fleet out of Ribos to contest Vasudan activities in Antarès. Tombaugh Station, one of the installations established at this time, became infamous during the Shivan Incursion. The captured Shivan warship Taranis was transferred to Tombaugh for research, only for the Shivan flagship Lucifer to make its first appearance, destroying Tombaugh before going on a rampage throughout the system and to the Antarès jump node to invade the rest of Terran/Vasudan space. In light of the system's resources and scientific curiosity, reconstruction efforts were initiated shortly after the end of the GTI insurrection, although it will be years before the system returns to its earlier level of economic activity.<br/><br/>Ribos is known to hold an unusual density of unstable $quotephasing$quote jump nodes. These nodes are only stable enough for transit for brief periods of time on an unpredictable schedule, making them all but useless for navigation. The intentional collapse of these jump nodes has been proposed in light of the Shivans ability to use jump nodes which are too unstable for Terran and Vasudan drives."
10445, "(fr)Betelgeuse"
10446, "(fr)The Betelgeuse system was colonized during the Fourteen Years War to lend logistical support to Vasudan forces operating out of Bêta Cygni. The system's most interesting feature is a moon with large deposits of high-quality fissionable material, which allowed the Bêta Cygni raiders to continue operating even as the GTA attempted to cut their supply lines. Most of the easily accessible deposits were harvested during the war, and in peacetime, most of Betelgeuse's population have returned to Bêta Cygni or elsewhere in the Empire."
10447, "(fr)<br/><br/>Since coming to power, the Antarès Federation have invested in mining operations in Bêta Cygni, since it contains resources which the Federation would otherwise have to import from the Alliance."
10448, "(fr)Ikeya"
10449, "(fr)Accessible only through the distant Ribos system, Ikeya sits on the edge of known space. An F-class main sequence star with a brown dwarf companion, Ikeya is interesting both for its distance and for its unusual asteroid belt, believed to be the remains of a massive crystalline object which had been captured and subsequently broken up by Ikeya's gravity well. Ikeya's population is an odd mix of scientists and businesspeople who value the loose regulations on the Frontière. Ikeya is also home to a popular racing circuit, with competitors flying custom-built ships through the system's crystal fields.<br/><br/>During the Shivan Incursion, the Shivan vanguard established cargo depots in Ikeya. This behavior raised many pertinent questions, chief among them how the Shivans came to be in the system in the first place. One concerning theory is the possibility of an uncharted jump node between Ikeya and Laramis or Ross 128, although detailed examination of the system has failed to identify any. At least one of these Shivan depots was found to be booby-trapped, a tactic which the Shivans would repeat several times early in the war. In spite of the trap, Shivan shield systems were successfully captured from one of the Ikeya depots, allowing Terran and Vasudan forces to finally fight back on even footing."
10450, "(fr)Ross 128 was the second system to be colonized by Terrans, but only barely. Initial colonization was spearheaded by a then-growing religious organization variously called the Zamanites or the Children of Umbra, who drew philosophical parallels between exploration and spiritual growth. While the habitability of the system's first planet had been suspected as early as the 21st century, the colony was held back significantly by difficulties in subspace navigation resulting from the star's low mass. As if to add insult to injury, the only new jump node found in the system was too energetic for contemporary jump drives to handle. The colony was largely left to its own devices until 2320, when the discovery of Kashiwabara supersymmetry allowed this node to finally be explored. Riviera Station was established to oversee it, bringing an end to the colony's semi-autonomous status$semicolon however, even today, Ross 128 has a unique culture as a result of its unusual history.<br/><br/>In January of 2335, Riviera Station was attacked and destroyed by unknown forces. Debriefing of the survivors revealed these ships to belong to a new species, which soon launched a number of unprovoked attacks against both Terran and Vasudan positions. Due to their aggressive nature and advanced weaponry, they were designated Shivans. Ever since then, popular sentiment has regarded Ross 128 as an inherently unsafe space, and both the GTA and PVN maintain a rotating $quoteShivan watch$quote with the assistance of the locals."
10451, "(fr)Laramis is one of a handful of systems which can be reached by subspace, but not observed directly from Earth. For many years, the jump node between Ross 128 and Laramis was thought to be unusable, but in 2320, new developments in jump drive technology allowed Laramis to finally be explored. Laramis is a fairly small system, having four planets, of which the second and third are habitable, and modest mineral wealth. While explorers from Ross 128 were quick to move in - the Zamanite religious group having retained their spiritual affinity for exploration - Laramis is mostly of interest for its jump node to Luyten 726-8A and the N362 neutron star.<br/><br/>Laramis was hurt significantly by the Shivan Incursion, although not directly. Shivan aggression in Ross 128 lead to an economic slump in Laramis, and eventually, civilian presence in the system began to fall off. Nowadays, there are no permanent habitats in Laramis, although STX Exploration maintains a limited mining presence."
10452, "(fr)N362"
10453, "(fr)The N362 neutron star was discovered shortly before the Shivan Incursion, and the first GTA science mission was still in the system when they attacked. As the only neutron star reachable via subspace, N362 is of immense scientific interest$semicolon in particular, gravitational and radiation flux around the star creates a highly unstable subspace environment, which has lead to several key discoveries in subspace field theory. It also makes the system a viable candidate for a Shivan entry point into GTA space, and while no permanent colony will ever be established in the system, there is always a GTA or PVN presence to keep an eye on N362, just in case.<br/><br/>The original N362 survey team created the Flail kinetic effect weapon by modifying sampling equipment to give their escorts a fighting chance should Shivans be discovered in the system."
10454, "(fr)Luyten 726-8A"
10455, "(fr)Luyten 726-8, also known as Gliese 65, held scientific interest long before Terrans developed space travel. A pair of highly variable flare stars eight and half light years from Sol, Luyten provided a treasure trove of knowledge for astronomers on Earth. Colonization of the system, however, was a long time coming, first due to the difficulty of reaching it - it was entirely inaccessible until the invention of a jump drive capable of navigating the Ross 128/Laramis subspace corridor - and then due to the binary's intense solar flares. However, the system's two planets and numerous asteroids held immense mineral wealth, and GTA Command, eager for any edge it could get in the ongoing war with the Vasudans, granted STX Exploration an ambitious contract to strip the system's raw materials to feed the Allied war machine.<br/><br/>The end of the Shivan Incursion and loss of the Sol jump node shocked every sector of the Terran economy, and Luyten was not immune. The demand for new warships dried up almost as quickly as the GTA's ability to pay for them, leaving STX with an array of expensive, highly specialized, and largely immovable infrastructure in a Frontière system pulsing with baleful electromagnetic radiation, and a government which had written them a bad check. Faced with a choice of bad options, STX's board of directors made the decision to continue operations in Luyten in hopes of finding a new market. This decision paid off as Vasudan reconstruction efforts kicked off, and a long-distance partnership with the Akheton Corporation kept the company's Luyten arm solvent long enough for Terran markets to stabilize."
10456, "(fr)<br/><br/>In the aftermath of Antarès' breakaway from the GTA, a coalition of scientific and industrial leaders, retired officers, and STX leadership, dissatisfied with Alliance policy but lacking a system to call their own, approached the General Assembly with a proposal. They asked that the Luyten system be granted autonomy in exchange for regular scientific contributions and cooperation on monitoring the Frontière for Shivan activity. This proposal was eventually accepted, and an eccentric collection of scientific, colonial, and industrial vessels became the first naval assets of the Luyten New Alliance. Their success in rapidly establishing a self-sufficient colony has piqued the GTA's interest, and a growing faction within the General Assembly now argue that their policy complaints must have had some truth to them. Others argue that the LNA could not have been successful without STX's assistance, but both groups agree that they've proven themselves a valuable ally."
10457, "(fr)Wolf 359 is a largely boring system, with few planets and fewer resources. Aside from an older-model comm relay, the only point of interest in Wolf 359 is the jump node to Alphard."
10458, "(fr)None"
10459, "(fr)Distances in subspace and realspace are only loosely correlated, and the ancient red dwarf called Barnard's Star is perhaps the most extreme example. By subspace travel, Barnard's Star is on the outer fringe of known space, but in terms of realspace distance, it's the second-closest system to humanity's birthplace. In 2083, long before the discovery of subspace travel, the Icarus II probe was launched on a fifty-year mission to reach Barnard's Star on massive fusion drives. After accelerating constantly for four years and reaching a decent fraction of the speed of light, the Icarus II suddenly dropped out of contact and was written off as a failed experiment. After the Luyten/Barnard's Star subspace node was charted, the probe was unexpectedly found to have reached Barnard's Star, intact apart from a burnt-out comm laser, and entered orbit of the largest planet, a bizarre crystalline body which is inexplicable under current theories of planetogenesis, and which has equally inexplicably acquired the popular name Sparkleantis."
10460, "(fr)<br/><br/>Informed by recovered Icarus II data and more recent surveys, LNA researchers have put forth multiple competing theories about the strange crystalline planet. Research missions are ongoing."
10461, "(fr)Alphard"
10462, "(fr)With only one planet, a gas giant called Aurelia far too close to the sun to be habitable, Alphard should be just another boring fringe system. However, the discovery of exoflora within the Aurelia's atmosphere, specifically evolved to harvest energy from Alphard's intense solar winds, has made it a fixture in both academic discourse and popular media. Similarities to the $quotefloaters$quote in the atmosphere of Beta Aquilae IV have raised questions about convergent evolution and the frequency of life throughout the galaxy. As beautiful as Alphard and Aurelia are, the solar winds make it difficult to maintain the Shivan monitoring systems required under General Order 21."
10463, "(fr)With only one planet, a gas giant called Aurelia far too close to the sun to be habitable, Alphard should be just another boring fringe system. However, the discovery of exoflora within the Aurelia's atmosphere, specifically evolved to harvest energy from Alphard's intense solar winds, has made it a fixture in both academic discourse and popular media. Similarities to the $quotefloaters$quote in the atmosphere of Beta Aquilae IV have raised questions about convergent evolution and the frequency of life throughout the galaxy. LNA missions to survey these organisms are frequent, although limited by the need to shuttle personnel and equipment through Wolf 359. The LNA are also working on a Shivan monitoring buoy better suited to survive Alphard's solar winds."
10464, "(fr)Dubhe"
10465, "(fr)Alpha Ursae Majoris, commonly called Dubhe, is a system of ill repute. Gravitational effects from the system's multiple stars and planets give it an unusually complex subspace topography: the jump node to Dubhe is fairly stable, albeit prone to moving about the system, while the jump node to Alphard phases in and out on an irregular schedule that renders it all but useless for travel. The recent discovery of a third jump node, leading to an unknown system and too energetic for even latest-generation jump drives to withstand, brought the system into the public consciousness as a possible Shivan origin point. If the Lucifer fleet could transit this node, it could easily have reached Ross 128 by way of Laramis$semicolon at the time, Fleet presence was minimal enough that they could have avoided detection. These concerns lead to the installation of sensor platforms and backup relays in all the systems between Dubhe and GTA space, although the systems in Dubhe have exhibited an unusually high failure rate, feeding into any number of conspiracy theories."
10466, "(fr) These concerns were revitalized in August of 2336, when Hammer of Light officers were found arranging discreet transit to Dubhe for unknown reasons."
10467, "(fr)<br/><br/>Since any Shivan attack out of Dubhe would have to pass through Luyten, Article IV of the Luyten New Alliance charter specifically compels the development of weapon systems designed to counter known Shivan tactics."
10468, "(fr)Dubhe holds a jump node to an unknown system. It is currently far too energetic for Terran or Vasudan jump drives to safely navigate, and is regarded as a possible Shivan origin site."
10395, "(fr)Delta Serpentis, locally known as Yamani, was the first system colonized by Terrans, and by far the most influential. With the collapse of the Sol jump node, it became the provisional capital of the Galactic Terran Alliance and the headquarters of the General Assembly. Nearly two hundred years of settlement have made the system into a garden, and its population of twelve billion Terrans rivals that of Sol itself. The $quotemini-Earths$quote of Janus and Elysia have been carefully terraformed into a close approximation of Earth's biosphere, but the system's crowning jewel is the waterworld of Sukhavati, which boasts a diverse array of native (albeit non-sapient) fauna in its large oceans. Humanity's ability to recover from the loss of Sol can largely be attributed to Delta Serpentis' economic base, although more forward-thinking members of the Assembly have argued that the resultant centralization introduces an existential risk."
10417, "(fr)After the colonization of Epsilon Pegasi, various groups rushed to colonize the newly discovered systems beyond its many jump nodes. The Alliance's attention was likewise divided between numerous colonial missions and new construction in Epsilon Pegasi. In the Polaris system, the Alliance's ability to govern the Frontière would be put to the test. Business interests in the system arranged to have relatively laissez-faire regulators installed in Polaris, setting up a chain of events that would lead to ongoing struggles with corruption throughout Polaris and its neighbors, Regulus and Sirius which last to this day.<br/><br/>Today, Polaris is the most respectable of the three systems in its sphere of influence. While the governments of Regulus and Sirius are openly corrupt and extremely weak, Polaris maintains a facade of respectability, allowing the criminal elements beyond it to interface with the rest of Terran society - and protecting them from outside oversight.<br/><br/>While many within the Alliance would like to reform Polaris, Regulus, and Sirius by force, the reality of the situation is more complicated. Many important companies, including fighter manufacturer Han-Ronald, are based out of these systems, and any disruption to them would have ramifications across the Alliance."
10418, "(fr)<br/><br/>There have been unconfirmed reports of ships out of Polaris lending logistical support to the Adhara Coalition."
10419, "(fr)Capella"
10392, "(fr)Sol"
10393, "(fr)In 2335, the destruction of the Shivan command ship Lucifer collapsed the Sol jump node in Delta Serpentis, cutting off nearly half of humanity from interstellar travel. The shocks to the Terran economic, social, and political landscape were immediate and overwhelming. For generations, Earth had been the center of Terran civilization. Humans still measured time in hours, days, months, and years. They named their ships after the mythological figures of ancient Terran civilizations, and their systems according to the constellations seen by ancient astronomers. The planet served as capital of the Galactic Terran Alliance, and the bulk of the Terran industrial base was located in the Sol system. Old ethnic and national identities still remained relevant even as new ones established themselves, and old forms of art and philosophy still resonated with modern audiences. The destruction of the Shivan flagship may have saved the Terran people, but in doing so, it ripped away their identity.<br/><br/>The fate of the Terran home planet remains open to speculation, though mainstream views paint a fairly bleak picture. As the center of an interstellar community, Earth could not survive in isolation without a radical transformation of its political and economic structures, but there is significant debate as to whether this transition will occurred peacefully or whether Solar society will collapse into anarchy. One school of thought posits a rehash of the Unification War, pointing to the deep cultural divisions between Earth, Mars, and trans-Jovian space. Others take a more optimistic view, citing the Juan de Fuca disaster and subsequent evacuation of the North American continent to offworld habitats as a model that could be adapted. Either way, even the most optimistic estimates view a multi-decade economic depression as all but inevitable.<br/><br/>Discovering the means to return home remains a high priority. The Alliance has invested heavily into long-overlooked research subjects, hoping to either restart the jump node or develop a novel means of faster-than-light propulsion. Meanwhile, proposals to establish radio- or laser-based communication platforms in Alpha Centauri are being considered, albeit with some bemusement from the system's largely Vasudan population. The ultimate success of such a project, of course, will depend on who's left to receive it."
10394, "(fr)Singular"
10420, "(fr)Capella is a rare example of a quaternary system, although two of the stars are small and relatively cool red dwarves. The other two are both giants, of which one emits significantly more energy than the other$semicolon since this star dictates the system's habitable zone, it is commonly, albeit inaccurately, referred to as $quoteCapella$quote as well.<br/><br/>The loss of the Sol jump node precipitated a paradigm shift in Terran economic thought. Over-reliance on a single system came to be seen as a dangerous gamble, and prominent members of the General Assembly began to advocate for a decentralization of Terran industrial capacity - the same sort of redundancy seen in spacecraft designs, applied on a larger scale. Due to its relatively high density of raw materials and easy access to the Polaris and Delta Serpentis arms of Allied space, Capella was selected for this initiative, and generous incentives were offered to any business willing to relocate operations to the system. Capella is now home to a Whiteside Construction regional office, along with a dizzying array of installations and habitats. While many see the $quoteCapella Initiative$quote as a success, and the system could certainly act as a bulwark against a disaster in Beta Aquilae or Delta Serpentis, such rapid settlement has outpaced the development of social services in Capella, and some fear that Regulus Syndicate operatives acting out of Polaris may step in to fill the vacuum."
10396, "(fr)Binary"
10397, "(fr)The Beta Aquilae system hosts three stars: Beta Aquilae A, also known as Alshain, and Beta Aquilae B, a small binary pair. It is the second largest Terran colony and the third system to be colonized by Terrans. However, unlike the adjacent Delta Serpentis system, Beta Aquilae's colony status was never a given. At the time, it was believed to have little in the way of natural resources or habitable planets, and no survey missions were undertaken until exploration beyond Ross 128 was stymied by the limits of contemporary jump drives. Interest in Beta Aquilae spiked when its first gas giant was found to contain unusual lifeforms whose metabolism produced several economically useful chemicals which were difficult to synthesize conventionally, and again with the discovery of two navigable jump nodes. Seeing the potential in the system, the fledgling GTA set up a permanent Fleet presence to support further development, and even to this day, Beta Aquilae is widely regarded as the industrial center of the GTA."
10398, "(fr)Trinary"
10399, "(fr)Vega"
10400, "(fr)The Vega star is orbited by an unusually dense debris disc and several dense, rocky worlds. During the Fourteen Years War, its position made it key battleground system, with both Allied and Imperial forces staking competing claims on the system's resources. During the opening years of the war, the GTA's 4th Fleet, led by the GTD Eisenhower, held the system quite handily, lending the GTA an early industrial advantage. This state of affairs was soon challenged by the PVD Typhon, which destroyed the Eisenhower and much of 4th Fleet in a sneak attack from Deneb. Terran reinforcements from Capella were able to hold the system, but barely, starting a series of border skirmishes that would see Vegan planets and moons change hands dozens of times. This bloody history lasted until the destruction of the GTD Amadeus by Shivan forces and resulting cease-fire.<br/><br/>Today, Vega is a uniquely divided system, with the PVE holding sway in the inner system, while the periphery is controlled by the GTA. Due to the placement of the system's jump nodes, this arrangement allows the GTA to access its colonies in Capella and beyond without infringing Vasudan space$semicolon however, the Capella node's orbit periodically takes it into Vasudan territory, providing no end of headache for the system's embassies."
10401, "(fr)Galactic Terran Alliance / Parliamentary Vasudan Empire"
10402, "(fr)<br/><br/>With the Adhara Coalition's declaration of autonomy, Allied warships passing through Vega have become an increasingly common sight, putting further pressure on the system's diplomatic situation."
10403, "(fr)The history of Deneb is complex and distinctly Vasudan. As Imperial shipping focused on exploiting Alpha Centauri's mineral wealth, an esoteric order of scientist-mystics turned their attention to Deneb, which hosted multiple Vasudan-habitable worlds but little of economic interest. Their application for a charter to colonize Deneb was ultimately granted with the proviso that, should any valuable minerals be discovered, rights to exploit them would revert to the central Imperial government. The subsequent discovery that a naturally occurring gas in Deneb VII's atmosphere could be used as a propellant in next-generation thrusters lead to a lengthy legal battle over the specific definition of $quotemineral$quote. An eventual ruling in favor of Deneb's local government saw the system become an economic powerhouse almost overnight. Unfortunately, the Fourteen Years War was not kind to Deneb, with a daring raid by the GTD Krios devastating both Deneb VII's infrastructure and the local PVN garrison. It is widely believed that the capabilities the Krios demonstrated directly lead to the development of the PVD Typhon as a countermeasure.<br/><br/>During the Shivan Incursion, the PVN expected the Lucifer fleet to strike Vasuda from Antarès. Instead, the Shivans used a previously uncharted subspace node to jump directly from Antarès to Deneb; when Vasudan forces attempted to follow, they found the Lucifer's passage had destabilized the node, forcing them to go the long way around. The GTD Galatea, GTD Bastion, and GTD Legion moved to assist the depleted Vasudan garrison in Deneb, leading to the loss of the Galatea and Legion while the Bastion withdrew to Vega. The Lucifer subsequently jumped to Vasuda. While the Terran response was unsuccessful, it did buy enough time for an evacuation fleet to reach Vasuda. The battle was also a diplomatic victory, burning away much of the distrust the Vasudan people had developed of Terrans during the Fourteen Years War. During the Galactic Terran Intelligence service's insurrection, Deneb would again be the site of a fleet action, with the GTD Soyakaze destroying the rebel flagship Hades in orbit of Deneb III. Due to the Hades' Shivan components, access to the wreck is currently limited to a select group of Terran and Vasudan researchers specifically chosen by the highest echelons of both governments."
10404, "(fr)The Vasudan species evolved on Vasuda IV, also known as Vasuda Prime. The Vasuda star, formerly called Bêta Hydri, is significantly larger and more energetic than Sol, rendering the majority of Vasuda Prime's surface a harsh, arid desert. Vasudan physiology evolved down radically different lines to our own, and that the only extant alien civilization in known space should arise on such a hostile world continues to intrigue Terran xenobiologists. Vasudan mythology, however, may provide an answer: every major Vasudan cultural tradition has some version of a myth concerning $quotegods from the stars$quote who visited their world in its infancy, and at least one form of the myth corresponds closely with the alien ruins discovered in Altair. Whether Vasudan civilization was uplifted by the Ancient civilization, or whether the similarities are mere coincidence, remains an active research topic.<br/><br/>The proximity of Vasuda to Terran space was a contributing factor in the misunderstandings that lead to the Fourteen Years War. However, it also proved to be a boon during the Shivan Incursion. When the Shivan Lucifer began its attack on Vasuda Prime, Terran forces out of Antarès rallied to assist in the evacuation, saving many lives and strengthening the cease-fire between both civilizations. While Vasuda Prime will never recover from the Lucifer's orbital bombardment, some of the system's outer-lying habitats were spared. Given the immense cultural significance the system continues to hold, it should not be surprising that these habitats remain in use even today."
10405, "(fr)The Alpha Centauri trinary system is emblematic of the difference between light speed and subspace navigation. At just over four light years away, it is, physically, the closest system to Sol. By subspace, however, it is on the far end of the Parliamentary Vasudan Empire. Alpha Centauri is a critical system in Vasudan history. It has multiple rocky planets rich in natural resources, balancing out the scarcity of resources on the Vasudan homeworld, and vast merchant fleets set out through the Vasuda/Alpha Centauri jump node to exploit these new worlds. In a very real sense, Alpha Centauri set the template for Vasudan expansion: while Terran colonists staked claims on every remotely habitable world, Vasudan explorers evaluated potential colonies based on what they could provide to the Empire as a whole.<br/><br/>Beyond its historical significance, Alpha Centauri holds some scientific interest as well. Its three jump nodes, leading to Vasuda, Sirius, and Aldebaran, are extremely close together, and attempting to explain this anomaly directly lead to the discovery of Kashiwabara supersymmetry. More recently, Terran engineers have converged on Alpha Centauri in an attempt to establish speed of light communication with Sol."
10406, "(fr)Following the destruction of Vasuda Prime, Aldebaran, also known as Alpha Tauri, became the capital of the Parliamentary Vasudan Empire. A binary system with a red giant primary, Aldebaran should be a difficult system to colonize. However, the system's first planet, a super-Jupiter gas giant with a complex system of moons, was formerly in the giant's habitable zone, and the remains of ancient life forms provide it with rich deposits of organic compounds useful in several advanced technologies. Meanwhile, a rocky world orbiting the system's binary companion has a similar environment to Vasuda Prime, making it an attractive destination for refuges from Vasuda. Additionally, the presence of PVN fleet assets in Aldebaran has been an effective deterrent for the Hammer of Light forces in Altair.<br/><br/>Aldebaran was once thought to be a quaternary system, but more recent observations have shown that two of the stars are actually part of the Hyades star cluster, not close enough to interact with the Aldebaran binary."
10407, "(fr)The Altair system is highly unusual in multiple ways. The Altair star rotates at roughly 286 kilometers per second at the equator, leading to the star being significantly flattened by rotational effects. More importantly, during the Shivan Incursion, ruins of an alien civilization were discovered on Altair IV. Archaeological records suggest that this civilization, designated $quoteAncients$quote, were destroyed by their own Shivan incursion eight millennia ago. Shortly before their destruction, the $quoteAncients$quote cached militarily useful technology on their former colony worlds - most critically, technology to track vessels through subspace, where Shivan shield systems do not function. This technology directly lead to the destruction of the Shivan Lucifer and the end of the Shivan Incursion.<br/><br/>Altair was formerly a minor colony of the Vasudan Empire, most notably holding the headquarters and primary shipyard of the Sahr Corporation. During the Shivan Incursion, much of the fleet in Altair defected to the Hammer of Light and drove out the loyalist forces, providing the Hammer with a well-stocked, well-defended base. Subspace geography should have left the Hammer of Light isolated in Altair$semicolon the presence of Ancient ruins, however, suggests that Altair may have an uncharted jump node, which the Hammer may have discovered and taken advantage of."
10408, "(fr) During a failed GTA/PVN assault on these shipyards, the HLC Taouret displayed unconventional FTL capabilities, which may provide an alternative explanation."
10409, "(fr) The discovery of the Lascaux network in Luyten has effectively confirmed this theory."
10410, "(fr)The discovery of the civilization designated $quoteAncients$quote raised several pertinent questions, including how they got there. The mainstream theory asserts the existence of an uncharted jump node from Altair to Ancient space. It is possible that the Hammer of Light may make use of this node as well."
10411, "(fr)The Sirius system was colonized shortly before first contact with the Parliamentary Vasudan Empire, and quickly became a key battleground owing to its proximity to both the PVE and the Han-Ronald shipyards in Regulus. The timing was highly unfortunate for the Alliance. The colonization push had brought countless civilians into the system, but the outbreak of the war precluded the establishment of social services or a proper local government. In a very real sense, there were two Siriuses: the war-torn battleground, and the neglected civilian population who'd been largely left to their own devices.<br/><br/>Today, Sirius is a deeply troubled system. The Regulus Syndicate criminal organization is almost as deeply entrenched in Sirius as it is in Regulus, and does a thriving trade in untaxed goods smuggled out of Vasudan space. Like in Regulus, the Syndicate has stepped up to provide social services in the absence of government support. Unfortunately, this level of criminal activity has profoundly warped the system's economy, and many citizens are mired in a form of quasi-legal indentured servitude, working on Syndicate-affiliated mining platforms and ore haulers to pay off debts. Due to its distance from the GTA, Sirius is even more entangled with criminal activity than Regulus itself, and the Office of the Attorney General has an entire committee working to $quotecrack the Sirius case$quote."
10412, "(fr)Merchant Guilds"
10413, "(fr)The history of Regulus is long and uncomfortable. Terran civilization expanded rapidly into the systems beyond Epsilon Pegasi, leaving them with relatively weak Alliance authority. Certain special interest groups were interested in capitalizing on the $quoteopportunity$quote, and found a convenient ally in the Alliance liaison office in Polaris, who, at the time, were operating with very limited oversight. In an act of blazon corruption, shortly before the end of the 23rd century, these officials granted a consortium of private businesses a very generous charter to colonize Regulus. Notable companies including the Han-Ronald Corporation, Diamant-Eye Pharmaceuticals, and Perun Reactor Systems almost immediately moved their corporate headquarters to the new $quotebusiness-friendly$quote Regulus colonies, while Alliance regulators, held back by political concerns in Polaris, were slow to respond.<br/><br/>In time, the workers of Regulus started to band together. A solidarity movement, calling itself the Regulus Workers' Syndicate after its decentralized nature, began to push back at corporate abuse. When Regulus' corporate leaders failed to provide services like security and adequate medical care, the Syndicate stepped in. When the corporations moved to suppress Syndicate activity, the Syndicate moved to protect itself. While the corporations had the advantages of better funding and the law on their side, the workers of the Syndicate had nothing to lose.<br/><br/>As ongoing conflict with the Workers' Syndicate cut into corporate profits, Regulus' corporate leaders decided they needed a new strategy. They agreed to some of the workers' demands in exchange for concessions. In time, they arranged to have more moderate leaders installed, until the Syndicate eventually became a shadow of its former self. What had been a symbol of workers' solidarity became just another of the system's quasi-legal guilds. Today, the Regulus Syndicate - the word $quoteWorkers'$quote has long fallen out of the name - still runs much of the shipping, healthcare, and security sectors in Regulus, and even legitimate businesspeople typically register with them for $quoteprotection$quote."
10414, "(fr)Quaternary"
10415, "(fr)The Regulus system holds an enigmatic jump node to an unknown system. According to current theories, it should be navigable, but all probe deployments through the corridor have lead to the loss of the probe in transit. Given the prevalence of criminal activity in Regulus, a number of conspiracy theories surround this node, although they are generally considered scientifically implausible."
10416, "(fr)Polaris"
