663, "(fr)Because your achievements distinguish you as an officer of the highest caliber, you have been promoted to the rank of Commander."
662, "(fr)Commander"
;;ships.tbl
923, "(fr)The Constellation type space-station is a multi-purpose orbital facility, used widely throughout Allied space. The first Constellations were launched in 2317 as zero-g manufacturing facilities, and many still serve in this role. However, like many early installation designs, the simplicity and low price of the Constellation has seen the basic design adapted to a wide range of needs. Constellation variants are often seen as outbuildings to existing facilities. Common roles include orbital dormitories, research outposts, shipyard control centers and customs depots.<br/><br/>The Constellation happens to share its name with a Unification War-era tactical carrier, which occasionally causes confusion."
924, "(fr)Pod"
10570, "(fr)Clamps"
10571, "(fr)TSSR Marcellus"
925, "(fr)The Marcellus refinery is designed in conjunction with the Bromios gas miner. In its basic configuration, it can refine hydrogen at the isotopic level to yield deuterium and tritium for fusion reactors, as well as isolate an excess of twenty economically significant gases through sequential or fractional differentiation. More complex models can be configured for more advanced procedures, such as LTLD (Low Temperature Liquid Differentiation), allowing them to isolate dozens more rare gases from extremely diluted feed stock. The primary difference between the Bromios and Zephyrus is that the Zephyrus includes these refining abilities internally."
926, "(fr)Main Tank"
927, "(fr)TSS Comet"
928, "(fr)Developed after the Great War, and continuously upgraded in the years that followed, the Comet supply depot is a modern, highly efficient space station, utilized by both the GTA and civilian organizations for the administration and protection of cargo depots, or as centers for commerce and trade. Although not itself armed, the Comet's sophisticated network of sensors and communications allow it to effectively control sentry gun networks. The station also carries attachment points for external docking platforms and TGas adaptor rings.<br/><br/>Economically, the Comet seems to be the beginning of the Mesa Corporation's attempt to diversify its portfolio after several quarters of poor performance in defense."
929, "(fr)TSS Adonis"
930, "(fr)The Adonis-class is an outdated space station. It is inhospitable and temperamental, with spartan accommodations and outdated computer systems compared to modern installations. The station is also indefensible, mounting only a single anti-asteroid turret which can barely track fighter-scale targets. The few Adonises still in use remain so because of some specific customization, typically scientific in nature."
931, "(fr)TSS Aurland"
932, "(fr)A space-borne hotel of civilian design, the Aurland is a popular choice for low-cost, low-maintenance, and relatively comfortable travelers' accommodations. Several are scattered around most major systems near important Lagrangian points and tourist attractions. The simple design of the Aurland makes it easily repurposed, and their use as observation posts, weather stations, and housing for refuges is almost as frequent as their original use as a hotel. RNI Systems has embraced this reality and maintains a stock of incomplete Aurland spaceframes for such purposes."
933, "(fr)TSS Nareos"
934, "(fr)Where the Aurland is a common, modest habitat prioritizing comfort and efficiency, the Nareos is a billionaire's getaway. Extravagant living quarters, ballrooms (both with and without gravity), professional servants, entertainers, and courtesans, and an integrated wildlife reserve all make the Nareos the dwelling of choice for wealthy travelers - and the permanent home of those who really want to show off. The population of the Nareos has fallen somewhat of late, as fewer people can afford to live on one in the post-War economic recession, and those who can are regarded with increasing scrutiny by an untrusting public."
935, "(fr)TSP Neta"
936, "(fr)Orbital prisons are considerably different than ground-based ones. While the cost of shuttling prisoners into orbit is a concern, the ability to totally isolate the prison's docking bays make escape a non-issue. Neta-class orbitals take this a step further, placing the hangar, bridge, and environmental controls in a separate hull entirely, which can only be reached by hermetically-sealed monorail. Controversially, the station's medical facilities are placed in the same section. Neta stations are an unfortunate necessity of the post-War era, isolating violent criminals that society can no longer afford to rehabilitate."
10572, "(fr)STX Exploration's Creidhne is, currently, a unique station, located in the Luyten system. Proprietary 'molecular forging' technology allows for extremely high extraction rates compared to conventional techniques. The technology was co-developed by STX and the LNA, and a small number of LNA technical observers can both be found here, responsible for ensuring everything goes smoothly as products are refined for export or further processing in STX's Aurora fabrication yard. It is legally unclear whether the LNA charter permits this sort of partnership without GTA involvement, but for now, the GTA has decided not to press the issue."
10573, "(fr)Shandong Industrial's Syracuse is a low-orbit mining station, designed to exploit resources on worlds inhospitable to Terran life. Each Syracuse is tailored to the unique needs of the mining crews it supports. Common features include atmospheric, tectonic, or volcanic warning sensors, as appropriate for the host planet, long-range communication transponders, and bays for mining and rescue shuttles. Among civilian spacers, any miner claiming to have worked a Syracuse is treated with a mixture of respect and awe. The majority of Syracuse stations can be found in Antarès, where they're almost synonymous with the Unnuit & Miller Mining corporation, but they can be found scattered across the galaxy, orbiting planets rich in rare materials and poor in ways to get at them."
10574, "(fr)Trenton Industries' Renault is a sophisticated station with a single goal: to push the boundaries of human exploration as far as possible. It accomplishes this goal with highly redundant systems, intentionally over-engineered life support, and a set of field-programmable fabrication units, allowing the crew to remain self-sufficient for months or even years if needed. The Renault's large hangar is intended to launch mining and survey ships, but was designed to be compatible with standard GTA strikecraft, allowing it to qualify for a tax rebate on dual-use equipment. While the Renault lives up to its stated goal of reliability, Trenton's experience with explorer ships has made them well aware of human frailty, and the station's communication system includes a dedicated bank of reserve fuel cells and a high-power disaster beacon."
10575, "(fr)From the megafauna of Adhara and the bententacled cetaceans of Delta Serpentis to the 'floaters' seen in some gas giants, extraterrestrial life has shown itself to be unexpectedly common - and where there is life, there are biologists. The Celina grew out of the need for a flexible laboratory capable of hosting specimens from an impossibly wide range of planetary environments. The station's inner volume is divided into numerous modules, each with individual settings for atmosphere, gravity, temperature, pressure, and a host of other variables. The end of the Fourteen Years War, and resulting peace with the only other known sapient species, only intensified demand for the Celina's capabilities - although describing a Celina's Vasudan guests as 'xenobiological specimens' is not recommended. Using Celinas as habitats in systems with sizeable mixed populations, such as Vega and Antarès, has been suggested, but is typically regarded as an inefficient use of a very costly design."
10576, "(fr)The Exarch is an old design with a unique place in Allied history. In the aftermath of the Unification War, the Alliance moved quickly to develop a strong economy and sense of galactic unity. The original Exarch Station in Delta Serpentis fed into both objectives, providing a strong symbol of unified Terran accomplishment. The station has been maintained over the centuries, with the loss of Sol, it became the capital of not only Delta Serpentis, but the entire Alliance.<br/><br/>Over time, the Exarch shifted from a unique station to a relatively common class. While the discovery of artificial gravity has rendered the large, counter-rotating gravity rings obsolete, newer Exarchs retain them out of historical and aesthetic concerns. Perhaps for this reason, the Exarch-class Borealis Station in Vega is a popular tourist destination for the system's Vasudan population."
10577, "(fr)Named for its lead designer's beloved daughter, the Aurora-class fabrication plant is STX Exploration's most advanced tool and the ultimate destination of the lion's share of their mining yield. The station's massive hull hosts dozens of workshops ranging from general-purpose manufacturing bays to highly specialized laboratories and cleanrooms. The manufacturing process is highly automated, and many of the crew are roboticists tasked with maintaining - and upgrading - the station's systems. Even a single Aurora has massive throughput, but they also extraordinarily expensive to create and operate$semicolon only two have ever been built, and STX currently has no plans to build more."
10578, "(fr)The Namid is a modular industrial platform designed for one purpose only - to smelt and refine vast quantities of celestial resources and package them for transport. Highly automated and devoid of defensive weaponry, the Namid is a ruthlessly efficient machine, turning large rocks into ingots of precious minerals, compressed hydrocarbons, and vital 'rare earth' metals needed by Terran industry. The Namid occupies a special legislative category within GTA regulations, exempt from both taxation and certain safety regulations, and Namid operators are seen as daring, almost romantic figures, risking their well-being to ensure human society can keep chugging along without Earth's resources. The reality is more complex: while corporations like STX Exploration and Exxon-Beckham rotate Namid crews and maintain dedicated medical facilities in case of accident, the 'asteroid pits' of Regulus and Sirius are crewed by de facto indentured laborers with comparatively limited protections.<br/><br/>While less flexible than a proper installation, the Namid can tolerate harsh environments such as the gravimetric flux of Sirius IV and the intense solar winds of Luyten 726-8. In a pinch, Luytenese ships have even been known to use them as improvised flare shelters. The design's minimalist, almost skeletal design has another advantage as well: an unloaded Namid has significantly less mass than the asteroids it processes, and can be broken down for transport aboard a modest handful of freighters. While the class is not without its flaws, its modular, efficient design means it is unlikely to be replaced for a long time."
10579, "(fr)The Lycaon is a class of orbital habitat with one primary purpose and a host of secondary ones. Derived from the technology that stabilized Earth's runaway greenhouse effect in the late 21st century, Lycaons are constructed in orbit of worlds on the verge of human habitability and serve to control networks of weather control satellites. Due to the long time needed to safely influence weather patterns, Lycaons are typically the first orbital construction, and so are designed to pull double duty as survey, communication, and command-and-control platforms, as well as permanent habitats."
10580, "(fr)With its eye-catching style and extensive inner volume, Europa-class stations are vacation spots first and foremost. Designed to compete directly with the Nareos, the Europa truly embraces its role as a spacefaring luxury hotel, with everything from its sweeping exterior curves to the positioning of its windows intended to constantly make its residents feel above the planet they orbit. Internally, the station's form-over-function design is extremely taxing on the crew, who need to coordinate carefully with the internal trams to get anywhere on time, and concerns GTA defense coordinators, who are acutely aware that a well-placed bombing run could snap the station in half. Even so, berth on Europa stations are highly prized, and seen as the last word in luxury among the Alliance's elite."
10581, "(fr)The Ignis is RNI System's experiment with a fully automated station. In its standard configuration, an Ignis can do little more than transmit its own diagnostics and pulse its station-keeping thrusters as needed$semicolon however, it comes with a highly configurable distributed computer network and both interior and exterior mounting points for specialized equipment. The Ignis remains a controversial design, with some praising the 'fire and forget' nature of setting one up while others criticize the relatively high price tag that comes with such extreme modularity. Nonetheless, Ignis units have found moderate success acting as comm relays, navigational markers, and other tasks for which the overhead of a human crew is significant. One surprising use is as a cargo transfer site, which requires only a software patch - the Ignis' computers being more than up to the task of keeping track of a few crates."
10582, "(fr)A high-energy physics lab designed by the LNA, Minerva is the only station of its type in existence. The station's core is a particle accelerator complex which the LNA uses for physics research. The extreme energy needs of Minerva's experiments would strain even the largest reactors in Allied space, so the LNA has devised an unusual solution. When power is needed for an experiment, a signal is sent to an antimatter pile a safe distance away, feeding a tightly focused X-ray laser which transfers power back to the accelerator. All ships jumping to Minerva are instructed to use a nearby navigational beacon and complete transit on standard drives, since a misjump while the beam is active could be catastrophic.<br/><br/>The LNA has made the Minerva specification available, earning it a TSS designation rather than an LNAi one, but so far, no one else seems interested in replicating this particular experiment."
10583, "(fr)The Empyrea is a research station specialized in biological experimentation. The station's long 'spine' is little more than a tramway, and maintains a high-quality vacuum outside the trams. This unusual configuration keeps the research module at one end isolated from the habitation and administrative modules at the other. As a further nod to safety, the research module is designed to break away in the event of emergency, while the habitat module carries a thruster suite and backup power generation, allowing it to be used as a lifeboat. Due to their association with potentially dangerous biological research, standing orders are for any Empyrea threatened by the Hammer of Light to be abandoned and scuttled before any capture attempt can be made."
10584, "(fr)The Jacmil is a research station designed for physics experiments. It shares several safety measures with the smaller Empyrea: in the event of emergency, any of its four research modules can be jettisoned, allowing for a melting-down experiment to do so at a safe distance. Jacmils are often employed for weapon and thruster research, and while they're usually kept far behind the front lines, any enemy action directed their way must be prioritized."
937, "(fr)TSh Mercury"
10585, "(fr)Shuttle"
938, "(fr)The Mercury-class shuttle has been in Terran service for the last six decades, in one capacity or another. Throughout that time, despite various upgrades, its mission has not changed. It is designed for short range, short duration transport of people and light cargo in space, and sometimes pressed into service as a lifeboat. The base model is unarmed and incapable of atmospheric operations and subspace travel, although its long service life has led to the creation of a multitude of variants, many of which have some or all these capabilities. The Mercury is one of the most common vessels of any type in the Terran military and civilian fleets. It is estimated that more than two hundred thousand of these ships have been created over the lifetime of the class, and many remain in service today."
939, "(fr)TDr Elepaio"
940, "(fr)Named after a species of bird from Earth's Hawaiian islands, the famed Elepaio is a multipurpose, fully automated platform capable of serving in roles as varied as uncrewed system exploration to basic-level scientific scans to surveys of enemy positions and patrol routes. Their small size and low cost make them the unit of choice of secondary communications buoys or even data couriers for high-value messages. While the design is decades old, having originally been developed as the Firebee training drone used by the various pre-GTA Terran blocs, its adaptability has ensured the design will be kept in service in various roles for years to come.<br/><br/>The 3301 repair drone is an additional derivative of the basic Elepaio design."
10586, "(fr)RNI Systems' Pèlerin is a small but highly adaptable scientific probe. The Pèlerin spaceframe itself is little more than a thruster package, computer core, and subspace comm system, leaving plenty of space for scientific payloads. RNI Systems sells a number of sensor modules intended for use with the Pèlerin, but has also published official specifications so anyone can create bespoke experiment packages. The semi-open nature of the Pèlerin has lead to it seeing widespread adoption within the scientific community, and is widely seen as a shrewd business move. For a time, RNI also sold a courier package, allowing a Pèlerin to make a single subspace jump with cargo in tow, but was ordered to stop after known pirate Lyra 'Slice' Cromwell used Pèlerin 'couriers' as improvised subspace weapons to ambush the prison transport Altmark and break out several of her associates."
