1011, "(fr)The Hauméa is a rare class of bomber designed and constructed by the paramilitary Second Dawn Society. While such heavy ordnance in civilian hands would be highly illegal in Galactic Terran space, the Hauméa was officially greenlit by the Luyten New Alliance in exchange for SDA cooperation in policing the system's Oort Cloud. Hauméas sometimes accompany Pélé patrols when encounters with Hammer of Light warships are expected.<br/><br/>The Hauméa is roughly comparable to the GTB Zeus. It is less maneuverable but slightly faster, and sacrifices ordnance capacity for armor. The Hauméa's most unique feature its offset triple-gun rack, which is typically loaded with an anti-hull cannon for supplementary firepower. The surprising success of this design against Hammer of Light assets in Luyten has attracted the attention of GTA observers.<br/><br/>A squadron of Hauméas was assigned to supplement Amanu Station's air wing shortly after the Society's entry into the Luyten conflict."
1012, "(fr)The TF Camma is small drone typically employed as a scout or swarm combatant. Offensive function is restricted to two burst-fire railguns apparently derived from the GTW-65 Railgun. No secondary banks or shields are evident. Like the GTW-65, Camma guns are significantly more effective against unshielded targets, or fighters with a breached shield quadrant. Adjust tactics accordingly.<br/><br/>Camma debris is highly heterogeneous. Analysis suggests that Cammas are accreted together from material surplus. Disturbingly, serial numbers from missing transports, shuttles, and fighters have been found in Camma debris.<br/><br/>The Camma is considered a Class C threat to transports and unsupported warships, and a Class D threat otherwise. In spite of its low classification, all personnel are expected to be vigilant. These raider ships exhibit exceptional subspace agility, and a single Camma rarely remains that way for long."
1013, "(fr)The Ankou appears to be the basic raider space superiority drone. As with all known raider ships, the Ankou lacks a pilot. Internal volumes that would be occupied with life support seem to be used for propulsion instead. This makes the Ankou swift and maneuverable for its size.<br/><br/>Like the smaller Camma, the Ankou's weaponry is munition-based. Scans indicate that the ship typically carries two hull-attack coilguns and a variant specialized in destroying subsystems. The Ankou possesses no secondary banks or shields. Bizarrely, no chaff or flare launchers have been detected. The Ankou relies exclusively on its small target profile and exceptional maneuverability for defense. The Ankou's flight characteristics have been compared to the dreaded Shivan Dragon class.<br/><br/>The Ankou is considered a Class C combatant. With their onboard disruptor weaponry, Ankou wings are often employed in capture operations."
1014, "(fr)The Dahut is a highly concerning stealth drone. Dahuts appear very stripped down compared to similar classes, lacking shields, adequate maneuvering thrusters, or even an onboard AI. They have only been seen escorting Ker-Ahes AWACS units, which seem to control them remotely. We believe these are intentional tradeoffs to enable the Dahut's stealth capabilities.<br/><br/>Previous experiments into stealth fighters have mostly focused on 'passive' systems, such as those carried by the GTF Loki. So-called 'active' stealth, wherein a spacecraft blends into surrounding space, have historically been regarded as highly impractical. Dahuts have two distinct advantages over conventional spacecraft in this area. Firstly, the Ker-Ahes' electronics warfare systems provide an environment that is easier to blend into than normal space. Secondly, delegating control functions to the AWACS frees up internal volume and power for the stealth systems. That the raiders could design such an effective and specialized system suggests they possess capabilities far beyond initial expectations.<br/><br/>Dahuts are fragile and poorly maneuverable, but their weapons pack considerable punch. Their magnetic projectile 'shotguns' are not only effective anti-hull weapons, but have a disruptive effect on their targets' electronics as well. A Ker-Ahes controlling a Dahut wing should be regarded as a Class A combatant, while the Dahuts themselves should be treated as Class B combatants. While uncontrolled Dahuts are helpless, they have occasionally been seen making unassisted jumps. Their destruction is therefore encouraged barring orders to the contrary."
1015, "(fr)With the possible exception of the Dahut stealth fighter, the Korrigan fighter is the most advanced craft fielded by the raiders. It is competent in a range of roles, which it achieves largely by virtue of packing many highly optimized systems on its large frame, although it is most commonly employed for fighter suppression. The Korrigan's armor and shielding approach GTA heavy fighter standards, while its maneuvering thruster suite is comparable to Allied superiority fighters. Offensively, the Korrigan carries the standard suite of raider projectile weaponry, as well as anti-shield missiles.<br/><br/>Korrigan fighters are a Class A combatant, and should be engaged with caution."
1017, "(fr)The Ys (pronounced 'eess') bomber was first encountered during an offensive at a major raider salvage operation, and represents a major increase in the raiders' capabilities. The Ys occupies a niche somewhere between the Terran Zeus and Medusa, carrying heavy ordnance but being maneuverable enough to have a chance of defending itself. Primary killing power is provided by a heavy version of the raider gauss cannon, which the Ys is capable of employing at extreme range, although it does carry traditional bombs as well. The Ys seems specifically designed to frustrate conventional interceptor tactics, laying down long-ranged fire to draw escort fighters away from their charges' point defense screens. Ys sometimes carry shield-breaker missiles as well.<br/><br/>Given its unusual weapons suite, the Ys is considered a Class B threat."
1018, "(fr)The Gradlon is a highly dangerous but relatively fragile strike bomber. Armed with four coilguns, two turrets, and deep ordnance bays, and equipped with thrust-vectored afterburners comparable to the PVF Horus, the Gradlon carries firepower rivaling the dreaded Shivan Seraphim bomber in a spaceframe scarcely more robust than a TSC 2 cargo container. Gradlons make little effort to evade pursuing fighters, often ignoring them until they have expended their ordinance, but its turret screen more than compensates, especially in formations of four or more. Some pilots have likened it to a down-scaled version of the TGs Marie-Morgane - powerful, but relying entirely on active defenses.<br/><br/>The Gradlon is considered a Class A threat, and demands a prompt response."
1019, "(fr)The Spriggan is a utility drone occasionally seen towing salvage. As an unarmed support vessel, the Spriggan is a Class F combatant, but their destruction as targets of opportunity is encouraged."
1020, "(fr)The Ker-Ahes is a raider command-and-control ship with a highly unusual design. First encountered engaging a Hammer of Light formation, the ship was initially designated as a corvette, a hitherto unused designation for a warship exceeding cruiser scale but less capable than a proper capital ship. Subsequent analysis of guncam footage has lead to the conclusion that the Ker-Ahes functions as a dedicated electronics warfare ship, with its long 'fins' serving as communication or sensor antennae. Our current theory is that the Ker-Ahes hosts the only actual Terrans (or Vasudans) among the raiders, and allows them fine-grained control over their drone fighters.<br/><br/>Typically, the Ker-Ahes would be considered a Class F combatant. Given its unconventional capabilities and its demonstrated effectiveness controlling drone squadrons, it has instead been designated a Class A combatant. Fortunately, the ship's 'fins' are easily destroyed by weapons fire, limiting its effectiveness, as seen in its first engagement."
