667, "(fr)Versatile space superiority fighter. Often doubles as an assault fighter. Large secondary payload."
669, "(fr)Han-Ronald's Apollo is a classic fighter dating back to the Fourteen Years War. During the opening years of the war, the Galactic Terran Alliance relied heavily on its fighter corps, which struggled to answer the Parliamentary Vasudan Navy's mainstays, the Mekhet and Neith cruisers$semicolon even Vasudan cargo ships were armed well enough to pose a serious challenge. The Apollo was designed to answer these ships in a fairly brutal fashion: massive swarms of Fury and MX-50 missiles coupled with enough hull plating to deliver them. While the Imperium had yet to introduce fighters of its own, it was expected that they would, so the Apollo was also given sufficient maneuverability to defend itself.<br/><br/>In spite of its age, the Apollo is still relevant. Current doctrine considers the Apollo a space superiority/assault fighter hybrid, and calls for them to be deployed in unstable situations where more specialized fighters are inappropriate. Apollos are the lightest fighters capable of carrying two separate secondary weapons, and many pilots load out with one bank of Hornet missiles for anti-shipping duty and another of dogfight missiles for self-defense.<br/><br/>The Apollo is considered a Class C combatant. It may be legally operated by registered system militias, but is otherwise forbidden to civilian operators. Unregistered Apollos are automatically subject to search and seizure under General Order 25. An unfortunate reality is that Han-Ronald's links to the troubled Regulus and Sirius systems have lead to numerous Apollo spaceframes being 'misplaced', and the ship's high missile capacity makes it a popular choice for Regulus Syndicate enforcers."
670, "(fr)Communication"
672, "(fr)Engine"
673, "(fr)Navigation"
674, "(fr)Sensors"
675, "(fr)GTF Valkyrie"
1016, "(fr)Interceptor"
676, "(fr)Good"
677, "(fr)Light"
678, "(fr)High speed recon and bomber-intercept fighter. Limited secondary capacity."
679, "(fr)Han-Ronald's Valkyrie is a radical redesign of the older Angel scout fighter. Compared to its predecessor, the Valkyrie features superior armor, speed, and performance, and tactical flexibility in the form of a second gun bank. A top speed greater than any Terran fighter ever produced has endeared the Valkyrie to interceptor squadrons like no other, though it suffers from limited weapons compatibility and a small missile bay. The Valkyrie's design is considered aged and not as adaptable as newer craft, or even the old Apollo. While there are no immediate plans to replace the Valkyrie, the Alliance is acutely aware of its limitations. In particular, the Phoenix series of missiles, a mainstay of Valkyrie squadrons, have been significantly held back by design constraints imposed by the Valkyrie's ordnance bay.<br/><br/>Like the Apollo, the Valkyrie is considered a Class C combatant. Also like the Apollo, Valkyries are occasionally seen in pirate hands, and these units should be destroyed whenever possible."
680, "(fr)GTF Hercules"
10470, "(fr)Assault Fighter"
681, "(fr)Average"
683, "(fr)Low max velocity offset by its tremendous offensive capabilities. High weapon capacity."
684, "(fr)The GTF Hercules is the third member of Han-Ronald's fighter suite. With six primary cannons in a 4-2 configuration and two spacious missile bays, the Hercules' offensive capabilities are easily sufficient to threaten any target of cruiser size or smaller. Thick armor and shields allow the Hercules to weather point defense fire, and some pilots have found success mounting Disruptor SDGs on the smaller primary bank for tactical flexibility. The Hercules does have several significant drawbacks, however. Slow acceleration and small afterburner reserves, limited maneuverability, and a large target profile make it an easy target for lighter fighters. Even so, many analysts consider the Hercules a key factor in the Alliance's defeat of the Shivan Incursion, citing its ability to shrug off the turret screen of heavy Shivan bombers which often confounded conventional interception tactics. The Hercules is expected to remain a mainstay of the Terran fleet for many years to come.<br/><br/>Given its overwhelming offensive power, the Hercules is considered a Class B combatant. Hercules units outside of GTA control are to be immediately confiscated or destroyed."
685, "(fr)GTF Ulysses"
686, "(fr)Excellent"
687, "(fr)Excellent all-around fighter. Offers superior maneuverability and a high top speed. Smaller missile payload than other GTA fighters."
688, "(fr)The Ulysses was the first joint effort between Terran and Vasudan research teams, a monumental sign of cooperation after fourteen years of war. The Ulysses is an excellent all-around fighter, and achieved considerable renown for countering the dreaded Shivan Dragon. The Ulysses does suffer from a frail hull and a small secondary bank, like the Valkyrie, but its thin target profile has helped many a pilot evade the primary weapons of a pursuing fighter. The Ulysses is currently in full-scale production, and is expected to eventually replace the Apollo as the Alliance's primary superiority fighter. It is also hoped that the Ulysses will break up the troubled Han-Ronald Corporation's near-monopoly on Allied fighter production.<br/><br/>The Ulysses is considered a Class C combatant, allowed in small numbers to registered militias but otherwise prohibited to civilian operators."
689, "(fr)GTF Myrmidon"
690, "(fr)Advanced prototype fighter, combines high primary firepower with flexible secondary loadout."
691, "(fr)RNI Systems is a relatively new player in the fighter world, describing itself as a corporation with future needs of the GTA in mind. Their superiority fighter design, the Myrmidon, differs radically from the Ulysses, and draws instead from the design philosophy of the old Apollo. RNI's engineers believed that a space superiority fighter in the post-Great War era would require an unprecedented combination of firepower and flexibility. OpEval has given the design high marks for speed, firepower, and loadout compatibility. It is faster than the Ulysses and carries even heavier armament than its inspiration, with six guns and three separate missile bays. This allows the Myrmidon to marry the primary firepower of the Hercules assault fighter with the flexibility of a much lighter ship. Some pilots more familiar with the Ulysses, however, bemoan the craft's large target profile and controls that have been described as $quotedrifty$quote."
692, "(fr)GTF Loki"
10471, "(fr)Recon"
694, "(fr)High"
695, "(fr)Low"
696, "(fr)High max velocity offset by its tiny payload. High weapon compatibility."
697, "(fr)The GTF Loki was developed by Galactic Terran Intelligence, ostensibly as a stealth reconnaissance fighter. A shielded reactor with highly optimized heat sinks, engine baffles, and carefully designed hull materials result in a fighter with a tiny sensor profile. During the insurrection within Galactic Terran Intelligence, the Loki's true nature was revealed: a highly dangerous superiority/interceptor hybrid capable of unpredictable stealth strikes in support of the rebellion's goals. While a crash upgrade of Allied sensor systems removed the Loki's stealth as a strategic consideration, the ship's excellent speed, maneuverability, and compatibility with advanced weapons like the Banshee allowed it to remain a credible tactical threat. With the defeat of GTI's Hades Rebellion, surviving Loki spaceframes were integrated into the GTA's fighter corps, although a high per-unit cost means production remains extremely limited. Lokis are considered too valuable to risk in battle, and typically deploy in their original reconnaissance role against pirate and Hammer of Light forces.<br/><br/>The Loki is considered a Class B combatant. However, very few security contractors can afford the sensor upgrades to break the Loki's stealth, so it is regulated as if it were a Class A combatant."
698, "(fr)GTB Athena"
10472, "(fr)Fighter-Bomber"
699, "(fr)Excellent for hit-and-run bombing. Good speed for its size, with a high capacity afterburner reserve."
705, "(fr)The Athena is a beloved but aging light bomber. The Athena is well-positioned to defend itself from enemy interceptors, but suffers from incompatibility with every modern torpedo in service with the GTA. The design remains relevant, however, due to its anti-subsystem capabilities, and still sees use delivering Stiletto turret-killer missiles to pave the way for heavy bombers and capture missions. Some squadrons have also had success employing the Athena as a missile boat to suppress enemy fighters at long range.<br/><br/>Like the Hercules, the Athena is considered a Class B combatant. However, given their effectiveness at disarming warship turrets, a limited number of Athenas have been made available to militia forces in systems threatened by the Hammer of Light. Rumors of Athena bombers in pirate hands persist, although it is generally believed that these are actually misidentified Mustang Bêtas, which have a similar exhaust profile."
706, "(fr)GTB Zeus"
10473, "(fr)Strike Bomber"
707, "(fr)Poor"
708, "(fr)Excellent for hit-and-run bombing. Can carry Tsunamis. Good afterburner supply."
709, "(fr)Like the Loki, the Zeus was fielded by Galactic Terran Intelligence during that organization's insurrection. Unlike the Loki, the Zeus has seen widespread integration into the GTA fighter corps, largely phasing out the older Athena. The Zeus was designed as a strike bomber, balancing raw firepower with maneuverability to get it in position. It lacks turrets and carries less ordnance than the comparable Medusa, but is still capable of mounting the Tsunami anti-cruiser bomb and the GTI-designed Serkr. Despite its checkered past, the Zeus is widely praised by current GTA military theorists who believe bombers derived from its lineage will become the mainstay of the Terran bomber corps.<br/><br/>The Zeus is considered a Class A combatant, and the sight of even a single Zeus in outlaw hands is considered a military emergency."
710, "(fr)GTB Medusa"
10474, "(fr)Heavy Bomber"
711, "(fr)Heavy"
713, "(fr)Medium bomber. Carries most missile types and one turret, but few cannons."
714, "(fr)The Medusa is the standard medium bomber of the GTA. Introduced to full service during the Great War, the Medusa was designed with the then-experimental Project Tsunami in mind, intended to carry the next-generation anti-cruiser warhead from the moment it was prototyped. While large and lacking in maneuverability, the Medusa's significant hull and shielding, in concert with its defensive turret, allow it to successfully engage enemy warships while being able to survive enemy fighters in pursuit. Vigorous debate has erupted, however, over the viability of the slow and ponderous Medusa compared to the newer, faster, yet more fragile Zeus. Some believe the design concepts of the Medusa will not survive the GTA's reconstruction, while others believe the Zeus's ability to defend itself is overstated and continue to favor a heavier, turreted design."
715, "(fr)Turret"
716, "(fr)GTB Ursa"
10475, "(fr)Fleet Bomber"
717, "(fr)Very Poor"
720, "(fr)Designed to annihilate capital ships and cruisers. Slow, but offers unparalleled assault bombing capability."
721, "(fr)Project Ursa was designed to carry heavy ordnance. Built around the experimental Harbinger warhead, the Ursa is the first bomber specifically designed to asymmetrically engage strategic targets with or without warship support. With large ordnance bays unsurpassed by any GTA bomber, more forward firepower than any Terran or Vasudan bomber, and exceptional durability, a wing of Ursas are easily capable of eliminating a destroyer-class warship, as they did to multiple Hammer of Light and Shivan destroyers during the Great War. While controversy reigns over the future of medium bomber designs, none in the GTA expect the Ursa to be replaced for at least three decades, although entrusting the spaceframe to the troubled Han-Ronald Corporation has raised some eyebrows."
10476, "(fr)Drone"
10477, "(fr)The Amazon Model IV combat drone was developed during the early stages of the Terran-Vasudan War to provide pilot candidates with a training target long before encountering an actual enemy. In the austere post-Sol era, the construction and destruction of so many drones has come to be seen as a wasteful luxury, and a series of simulator programs has been developed to provide basic training instead. As Amazon construction winds down, the class is becoming more and more seen only on purely virtual battlefields. This leaves a large number of drones remaining in the GTA's inventory, however, and numerous programs to put them to use have been proposed. Some Amazons have been repurposed for scientific survey, while others are used as test targets. Strangely, investigation into the Galactic Terran Intelligence uprising discovered a large number of Amazon spaceframes at various rebel sites.<br/><br/>Proposals to field a combat-effective Amazon variant have been repeatedly denied under the Second and Third Conventions on Autonomous Weapon Systems, although small numbers of armed drones overseen by human operators are permitted to civilian security providers. They are also sometimes seen in pirate hands."
10478, "(fr)The Amazon Advanced Model VII is an uncrewed training drone used by the GTA for subsystem and large target training. Much like the basic Amazon, efforts are ongoing to deprecate the Amazon Advanced in favor of simulated training. The question of what to do with the backstock of Amazon Advanced units is likewise relevant. While the basic spaceframe is derived from the Chronos freighter, with minimal systems and no crew, the Amazon Advanced is not a reliable cargo hauler. Even so, smuggler and pirate groups sometimes view the risk of losing a crate as preferable to the risk of getting caught."
722, "(fr)GTS Centaur"
10479, "(fr)Support Ship"
724, "(fr)The Gulisano Group's Centaur support ship carries spare ordnance to rearm Allied fighters and bombers, and sophisticated electronics to diagnose and repair damaged subsystems. The design was introduced early in the Fourteen Years War and almost immediately proved its worth, helping GTA fighters outlast the swarm tactics favored by the PVN at the time. The Centaur has proven itself to be highly effective, although with the rise of heavy bombers like the Medusa and Ursa, several new designs with increased warhead capacity have been proposed. The Centaur's tendency to explode violently when fired upon is well known, and at least one proposed replacement features a breakaway ordnance bay to mitigate this tendency. How such a system will function in practice remains to be seen.<br/><br/>As of 2323, Centaur pilots are commissioned as Lieutenant, Junior Grade, giving them some authority to advise rookie pilots on maintenance procedures."
10480, "(fr)The Centaur support ship has been resupplying Terran fighters and bombers since the early Terran-Vasudan War. Fast and maneuverable, the Centaur can quickly dock with fighters and bombers in order to refill their ordnance bays and repair any damaged subsystems. When destroyed, however, the sheer number of warheads carried on one of these ships tend to present a danger to all nearby craft. While effective in its duties, the GTA has been considering replacing the Centaur with a ship capable of carrying even more warheads, allowing for a longer period of resupply before needing to exit the battlefield."
10481, "(fr)The GTS Hygeia is the fleet's newest Terran support ship. It is fast and maneuverable, a necessity when trying to dock with fighters in the heat of battle. Triton Dynamics designed the Hygeia with huge cargo bays for munitions storage, plus the latest magnetic-stasis delivery system for quickly re-supplying combat craft with missiles and bombs. The Hygeia's repair facilities are driven by neural-net AI, for ultra-fast system diagnostics and repair. The high number of warheads carried by the Hygeia makes it a dangerous ship to be near when it blows up."
725, "(fr)GTT Elysium"
10482, "(fr)Transport"
726, "(fr)The Elysium, or 'Shoebox', is a transport with an unusual role in Terran history. With the formation of the Galactic Terran Alliance after the Unification War, humanity turned its attention to building a galactic economy. In an unusual move, the nascent GTA published designs for a variety of simple, rugged craft suitable for both military and civilian use and ordered dozens each from multiple major suppliers. This lead to every Allied system having at least one shipyard capable of producing highly efficient, mutually compatible ships and parts, providing a much-needed jump-start to the unified society's post-war economy. The Elysium is one such design, and Elysium units have seen used as civilian shuttles, scientific monitoring stations, search-and-rescue ships, and boarding transports for Alliance Marines, with one company even offering an 'orbital ballroom' variant of the design. While the Elysium will remain popular in civilian circles for years to come, its defensive capabilities are very limited, and the GTA hopes to phase it out from frontline roles."
727, "(fr)GTT Argo"
729, "(fr)The Argo is a next-generation transport intended to replace the Elysium in GTA military service. While possessing similar qualities to the Elysium, such as ease of upgrades and exceptional reliability, the Argo is significantly larger and more durable, with only a modest cost increase. The Argo's spaceframe is completely unlike the Elysium's, however, and the GTA has offered financial assistance to help contractors retool their assembly lines to Argo specifications."
730, "(fr)GTM Hippocrates"
10483, "(fr)Auxiliary"
10524, "(fr)Explorer"
733, "(fr)Radar Dish"
734, "(fr)GTFr Poseidon"
10484, "(fr)Freighter"
735, "(fr)The Poseidon is a small but heavily defended freighter developed by STX Exploration. The opening stages of the Terran-Vasudan War quickly demonstrated the limitations of the then-standard Chronos freighter. Taking inspiration from the Vasudan Ma'at and Satis, STX designed the Poseidon with raw tonnage as a secondary concern to self-defense. With four well-placed turrets, Poseidon formations foiled Vasudan fighter operations in much the same way Ma'at formations foiled Terrans, and while the development of fighter shields has shifted the balance, the Poseidon's guns still represent valuable fire support for convoy escorts.<br/><br/>With growing pirate and Hammer of Light activity, demilitarized Poseidons are becoming increasingly common in long-haul civilian operations. While GTA Poseidons typically carry the standard TC 2 cargo container, or its uparmored successor, the TSC 2, those in civilian service are often modified to support older containers like the TC A09 and specialized containers like Subach-Innes' TGas-1. A conversion kit for the TAC 1 armored container is also available, providing increased payload, survivability, and interoperability with the Chronos, although the GTA would rather deploy multiple Poseidons instead."
737, "(fr)TC 2"
10485, "(fr)Cargo Container"
738, "(fr)TC 2s are the standard Terran military cargo container. They have the necessary systems needed to preserve whatever cargo is inside it, regardless of external conditions. TC 2s are cheap to manufacture and heavily used throughout the GTA, but are being supplemented if not replaced by the TSC 2, which is much more durable given the increase in fighters' and bombers' firepower."
739, "(fr)TSC 2"
740, "(fr)The TSC 2 is a development of the older TC 2 cargo container. A small amount of internal space is sacrificed for redundant hull plating, making the TSC 2 significantly more durable than its counterpart. While not as durable as the TAC 1, the TSC 2 is usually the GTA's container of choice for carrying cargo with any military value."
741, "(fr)TTC 1"
742, "(fr)The TTC 1 is a civilian cargo container intended for use in research purposes, or alternatively, zero-G development operations. TTC 1s are essentially miniaturized laboratories, which has made them popular both with the GTA and corporate manufacturing groups. Being a research container, the TTC 1 is fragile, and its valuable equipment often makes it a target of enemy attacks."
744, "(fr)GTFr Chronos"
745, "(fr)The Chronos is a freighter design of the same vintage as the Elysium. Like the Elysium, the Alliance arranged for major companies across its space to set up Chronos assembly lines, ensuring a ready supply of simple, robust spaceframes and spare parts. The design was compared to old Earth semi-trucks: fast, reliable, and prevalent. With a single turret and compatibility with the TAC 1 armored cargo container, the Chronos was adequately defended from the fighters of the time, but by the time of the Fourteen Years War, it was hopelessly outmatched by contemporary Vasudan fighters. Even so, the design's simplicity, readily available spare parts, and large cargo capacity compared to the Poseidon and Elysium have kept it flying, and it likely will continue to do so in civilian circles for years to come. Among the GTA military, the new Triton has started phasing out the Chronos in the bulk cargo role."
746, "(fr)Bridge"
747, "(fr)TAC 1"
748, "(fr)The TAC 1, commonly called the Tac One by most pilots, is a heavy armored cargo container intended for use in carrying volatile, dangerous, or military-grade equipment. Tens of thousands of TAC 1s have been produced since its inception, and the design has regularly seen use on the frontlines of every major Terran conflict since the Unification War. Given the increasing firepower of modern fighters, the container's armor has become less useful over time, although away from the front lines, it's still popular for its relatively large capacity."
749, "(fr)GTFr Triton"
750, "(fr)In the post-Great War economic slump, the GTA put out a request for a new bulk freighter to save costs, and Triton Dynamics answered with a philosophy of 'bigger is better'. The resulting GTFr Triton, along with its new cargo container, the TC-TRI, won the contract after considerable debate among Alliance brass. Some saw the design's reliance on a dedicated container as a wasteful luxury, while others viewed its extremely limited defenses - two small turrets which don't even cover the ship's entire length - as reckless, even negligent. The math tells a different story. Between its cargo container and internal storage, a single Triton can carry almost as much cargo as ten Poseidon freighters, while costing only as much as four. Its large size also allows for a much more expansive engineering section, and Triton crews can patch up engine breakdowns that would leave a Poseidon or Chronos calling for a tug. Triton Dynamics may have been wise to name the class after their own company, since the Triton seems likely to be center stage among freight contracts for years to come."
751, "(fr)TC-TRI"
752, "(fr)The TC-TRI container is intended to work alongside the GTFr Triton, and no other ship in Allied space can effectively move the container. Internally, the TC-TRI's volume is divided into a number of internal partitions, which can be resized and reconfigured to accept a wide range of cargoes. The design is even rated for human habitation, and a proposal to create a variant which functions as a mobile repair shop is being considered."
753, "(fr)GT Explosive Charge"
889, "(fr)THIS NEEDS NO STINKIN TECH DESCRIPTION!"
754, "(fr)GTSC Faustus"
755, "(fr)The Faustus-class 'science cruiser' is a common sight among the GTA's scientific, engineering, and military divisions, and some have been sold to civilian interests as well. The highly versatile spaceframe is typically configured as a mobile laboratory or survey platform, but can also be employed as a communications terminal, navigational waystation, or even hospital ship. It was on board a Faustus during the Great War that Shivan shield technology was reverse-engineered from a captured Shivan fighter, and the Tsunami bomb and Avenger cannon were also both developed on Faustus vessels. While critical to Terran development for over three and a half decades, the Faustus is poorly armed, poorly armored, and slow by modern standards, making it a prime target to any hostile forces."
756, "(fr)Solar Panel"
10486, "(fr)The Whiteside is a deep-space survey vessel. Unlike the more common Faustus, a significant portion of the Whiteside's internal volume is set aside for long-term habitation, although it shares its rival's modular laboratory design. The original Whiteside was a unique vessel, commissioned by the GTA with the specific purpose of locating the starting point of the Shivan Incursion. When it came back empty-handed, growing pressure for an answer to 'The Shivan Question' lead to the commissioning of several more Whiteside-class ships for broader analysis. Most are employed in subspace survey missions, but the GTSC Bifrost has recently deployed to N362, in hopes that data gathered on the system's turbulent subspace environment will help repair the Sol node in Delta Serpentis.<br/><br/>The Whiteside shares its name with its manufacturer, Whiteside Construction. Ostensibly, the design is actually named after the xenoarcheologist who lead the reverse-engineering of Ancient subspace tracking technology, and the similarity is merely a coincidence. Some, however, believe that the name was intentionally chosen to distance Whiteside Construction's public image from warships like the Orion."
10487, "(fr)Sensor Panels"
10488, "(fr)The Zephyrus is a gas miner derived from the civilian Bromios. Like its smaller cousin, the Zephyrus harvests valuable gases from interstellar nebulae and gas giants, most critically the deuterium required for fusion drives. Its massive spaceframe, ponderous cruising speed when fully loaded, and thin armor means the class is rarely seen anywhere near the front lines."
757, "(fr)GTC Fenris"
10489, "(fr)Cruiser"
758, "(fr)The Fenris warship design dates back to the early days of the 14 Years' War. Contemporary Terran warships had proven themselves outclassed by the Vasudan Neith and Mekhet cruisers, and the Fenris was fast-tracked as a rapid-response answer. The ship is built around a mortar turret mounted on an offset pylon, allowing for target acquisition from many angles. Much of the spaceframe's internal volume is dedicated to feeding this weapon. While a powerful offensive option with good real- and subspace maneuverability for its size, the Fenris has limited staying power and requires careful escort, a problem rectified by the newer Leviathan. While the Alliance is accepting bids for a new strike cruiser design, the Fenris remains effective in its intended role even on modern battlefields. One notable example, the GTC Orff, provided critical fire support during the destruction of the GTI rebellion's flagship, the Hades."
759, "(fr)GTC Leviathan"
760, "(fr)If the Fenris cruiser is a glass cannon, the Leviathan is a stone wall. Even before the first Fenris rolled off the assembly line, the Alliance admiralty was aware of its limited staying power, and commissioned a defensively oriented cruiser class to complement it. The Leviathan uses the same core spaceframe as the Fenris, but has proportionally more space dedicated to armor plating and the power generation needed to move it. The Leviathan provides a critical defensive element at installations across Allied space, and has even been employed as a supporting element in operations deemed unsuitable for the more fragile Fenris.<br/><br/>Nankam Aeronautical subcontracted the Leviathan's armor to strikecraft manufacturer Han-Ronald, an unconventional but surprisingly prudent decision. Drawing on their experience with the Hercules, Han-Ronald designed a network of independent armor modules, each capable of limited damage control similar to a fighter's ability to repair damaged subsystems. Networked systems throughout the hull provide real-time armor status to the Leviathan's helm, allowing the pilot to expose undamaged sections to the enemy. While effective, this technology is held back by its exorbitant price tag, and neither Han-Ronald, Nankam, or the Allied admiralty are in a hurry to revisit it."
761, "(fr)GTD Orion"
10490, "(fr)Destroyer"
762, "(fr)At just over two kilometers in length, the Orion-class destroyer is the largest, most capable warship ever produced by the Galactic Terran Alliance. There is no more important symbol of Terran pride than an Orion patrolling a system and ensuring safety. With multiple onboard squadrons, a quartet of Howell torpedo launchers, and dozens of point defense stations, the Orion is both a strategic carrier and a deadly ship-to-ship combatant. Very few Orions were lost during both the Terran-Vasudan War and the Great War, their design proving effective against both the Vasudan Typhon and Shivan Demon destroyers, though the loss of each vessel was a tragedy beyond compare. Peace is expected to see the Orion supplemented by a lighter, cheaper destroyer class, but to suggest the design will be removed from service any time soon is considered sacrilege by most military analysts.<br/><br/>The Orion is considered a Class S combatant. Whiteside Construction typically employs over two dozen subcontractors on each Orion spaceframe, and the commissioning of a new Orion has wide-reaching implications for the galactic stock market as various corporations compete to get their systems on board."
763, "(fr)Fighterbay"
764, "(fr)GTI Ganymede"
10491, "(fr)Installation"
765, "(fr)The Ganymede is a large drydock operated by Whiteside Construction on behalf of the GTA navy, merchant marine, and science corps. All systems with a permanent Fleet presence has at least one Ganymede for repairs. Each of the Ganymede's outer docking arms can service a cruiser or auxiliary ship, while the central umbilicals can host vessels up to destroyer scale. While primarily employed as a repair facility, the Ganymede also provides retrofitting services, allowing aging designs to be upgraded with modern weapons, systems, and engines. The station is even capable of transiting subspace with the assistance of a Triton, Atlantis, or similar large freighter."
766, "(fr)Storage"
767, "(fr)Connection"
768, "(fr)Hose"
769, "(fr)GTI Exos"
770, "(fr)The Exos is a retrofitted installation design dating back decades to the conflict between various powers in Sol. Lightweight and much cheaper than an Arcadia, Exos installations are a common sight in fringe and Frontière systems, where they can quickly be erected as a hub for new infrastructure. They have limited hangar capacity and are often home to a militia unit, although GTA forces prefer the more capable Asteria."
771, "(fr)Tower"
10492, "(fr)Currently unused. Check Closeup Positions in the tech room if added later."
852, "(fr)Reactor"
772, "(fr)GTI Endymion"
773, "(fr)The Endymion line of stations were deployed in contested systems during the Fourteen Years War. Nestled away in secluded areas, such as the Iraklion Corridor in Antarès and within the upper atmosphere of Vega IV, the Endymions were shrouded in secrecy, and their positions heavily classified to keep them away from PVN raiders. Their purpose was simple, if ambitious: providing a secret location behind enemy lines for espionage and covert ops should their host systems fall. Rumors persist of elements of the GTI Insurrection taking refuge on Endymion platforms, but so far, none have been substantiated. Expeditions to purge Endymion computer systems of potentially sensitive data are planned, but a low priority given their inaccessibility. Until then, unauthorized entry is prohibited."
10493, "(fr)Signal Receiver"
870, "(fr)Tank"
10494, "(fr)The Veles is a large warehouse station. The first Veles was constructed to foster expansion into Beta Aquilae, and demonstrated an almost spartan dedication to its role, boasting a cavernous hangar capable of onboarding entire freighters, cargo elevators and cranes to process a diverse range of goods, then-sophisticated navigational transponders, and little else. The design proved surprisingly successful, and the GTA commissioned over a dozen of them in the coming years. Unlike the Elysium and Chronos introduced by the same program, history has not been kind to the Veles. The outbreak of the Fourteen Years War demonstrated the danger of consolidating so much trade in one place, and by the war's end, seven out of the fifteen active Veles units were destroyed by Vasudan raiders or scuttled to avoid capture. The rise of the Arcadia, which was much better equipped to defend itself, and deep-space storage depots, which could avoid danger simply by going undetected, spelled the end of the Veles in its original role, although surviving units have shown themselves well-suited for use as deep-space waystations and foundries for small craft."
10495, "(fr)Aux Bay"
10496, "(fr)Shuttle Bay"
774, "(fr)GTI Acheron"
775, "(fr)The Acheron is a proposal for a large mortar platform, intended to blockade jump nodes and provide supplemental anti-warship firepower to critical infrastructure. While the proposal was accepted, no Acheron units are listed in the GTA's Order of Battle."
776, "(fr)GTI Asteria"
777, "(fr)The Asteria is a station based around a lighter Arcadia-style concept. Intended for commerce and trade, its nine docking points and the ability to station a squadron of patrol fighters allows it to serve well as a trade hub in a system. Whiteside Construction reportedly dislikes the Asteria, citing both a relatively low profit margin and safety concerns surrounding its relatively fragile hull. Nevertheless, it fulfills an important economic niche which the larger Arcadia cannot, and the Alliance continues to commission Asteria units in contested sectors, where their fighter wings can provide much-needed relief from pirate activity."
778, "(fr)GTI Arcadia"
781, "(fr)The Arcadia is the largest installation in Terran space. The establishment of an Arcadia in a system is a major event, and marks the transition from fledgling outpost to full-fledged colony system. These massive installations serve as the system's civic hub while terraforming efforts are underway, and even after planetary settlements are established, they remain critical commercial gateways and communications centers. Often, a system's Arcadia is also home to its militia, and military operations, civilian security, and scores of shuttles, transports, and survey ships all call it home. Home to scores of fighters, bombers, transports, and resupply ships, an Arcadia is always deemed a safe haven for a convoy of ships returning from battle. While the Orion is the symbol of Terran power, the Arcadia is the shining beacon of stability."
10497, "(fr)Forklift"
10498, "(fr)table"
10499, "(fr)Asteroid Installation"
10500, "(fr)This clandestine facility is built into a cluster of asteroids in the far fringe of the Oort Cloud. Employing a similar philosophy as the SDA asteroid bases, most of the station is tucked away inside the asteroids, with minimal superstructure aside from a network of low-visibility causeways. Vostok was unknown to the GTA until Captain Varner's testimony, after which it was raided by Alliance Marines, revealing it to have been the center of research for ADEIS's controlling AI. It appears that the station was abandoned after infighting regarding the governance of the project."
10501, "(fr)Door"
10502, "(fr)Force Field"
10503, "(fr)Fan"
859, "(fr)Small Tank"
782, "(fr)GTSG Watchdog"
783, "(fr)Once the standard in sentry turrets for the GTA, the Watchdog has become largely obsolete on modern battlefields, and the GTA has come to regard it as little more than a glorified sensor platform. It mounts a pair of plasma turrets with limited ability to track targets, but can still be an effective deterrent to the older-model fighters seen among pirate outfits.<br/><br/>The Watchdog is regarded as a Class E combatant, and a Class D combatant when four or more are present."
784, "(fr)GTSG Cerberus"
785, "(fr)The Cerberus is a block upgrade of the old Watchdog sentry gun, featuring the same turret system seen on Medusa and Ursa bombers and molybdenum reinforcements at key points on its hull. More importantly, the Cerberus' targeting algorithms have been completely rewritten. The computer systems in a Cerberus formation coordinate much more effectively, with one platform assuming a command-and-control role over networked guns. This occasionally provokes legal challenges under the Third Convention on Autonomous Weapon Systems, and the GTA recommends that any facility, military or civilian, using Cerberus platforms for defense maintain human oversight as a legal and practical safeguard.<br/><br/>The Cerberus is considered a Class D combatant, or a Class C combatant when four or more are present. Unfortunately, upgrade kits sometimes find their way into pirate hands."
10504, "(fr)The Némésis is a field-portable electronics warfare platform. It was developed at the same time as the Watchdog sentry and intended as the second part of a defensive suite, addressing one of the major limitations of the sentry gun concept - guided missiles. The technology didn't pan out, however, with early Némésis prototypes being more effective at throwing off the already dubious aim of their Watchdog partners. Interest in the Némésis occasionally picks back up, most recently in the form of a fighter-deployable variant. Development so far has struggled to tune the Némésis so that it consistently jams enemy weapons without impacting friendly units as well."
786, "(fr)GTEP Hermès"
10505, "(fr)Escape Pod"
787, "(fr)The Hermès escape pod has been used since the destruction of the GTD Goliath over thirteen years ago. Now a standard on a variety of Terran ships and installations, the Hermès typically carries twenty personnel with little room to spare. With no afterburner, no turrets, and no shields, a Hermès is good for getting away from an exploding ship or station and little else."
885, "(fr)GTNB Pharos"
10506, "(fr)Platform"
10507, "(fr)The Pharos-class navigational beacon is named after the historical Phare of Alexandria, and fulfills a similar purpose. Pharos buoys relay navigational data across the subspace barrier, helping ships arrive safely and avoid collisions. The basic spaceframe is flexible and often upgraded with sensor and comm systems as needed."
788, "(fr)PVF Anubis"
10508, "(fr)Skirmisher"
789, "(fr)Lowest power Vasudan craft. Offers little in the way of offensive or defensive capabilities. Best used in swarm situations."
791, "(fr)The Parliamentary Vasudan Navy's Anubis is the oldest fighter currently in use by either the PVN or the GTA. During the Terran-Vasudan War, the Anubis was feared by Terran pilots due to its tendency to appear in overwhelming numbers. While the Anubis' top speed and maneuverability keep it from being entirely obsolete, its small spaceframe barely has room for a shield generator, and is incapable of mounting afterburners. The Anubis sees more use among the Hammer of Light terrorist organization, where it is often flown in a kamikaze role.<br/><br/>The Anubis is considered a Class D combatant, unless operated by HoL in the presence of Allied shipping, in which case it is considered a Class C combatant."
792, "(fr)PVF Seth"
793, "(fr)Slow and sluggish, but heavily armored. Has high afterburner speed. Useful for hit and run attacks. High payload capacity."
794, "(fr)The Seth was designed by Vasudan engineers during the Fourteen Years War to counter the Terran Apollo. The Seth is the slowest fighter in the Vasudan fleet, but is also compact, carries a significant amount of ordnance for its size, and has exceptionally powerful afterburners that can more than double its speed. As joint Terran and Vasudan operations became common during the Shivan Incursion, the Seth was naturally compared to the Terran Hercules. Both fighters are durable, and both can provide an effective standoff threat when loaded out with anti-fighter missiles, but the similarities end there. Lacking the Hercules' four-gun bank, the Seth typically carries swarm missiles or Fang unguided rockets as a hull-attack option, adopting a hit-and-run attack strategy that leverages its afterburner well. The Seth can more easily escape an unfavorable dogfight, but the Hercules' extra guns can achieve devastating snap shots which the Seth is incapable of. Both designs have their merits, but the Hercules is more self-sufficient, while the Seth favors a combined-arms approach.<br/><br/>The Seth is Mekhu Enterprises' only foray into fighter design since the Anubis, and for the time being, they seem content to let it remain that way.<br/><br/>The Seth is a Class C combatant. Unfortunately, they are a common sight among Hammer of Light squadrons."
795, "(fr)PVF Horus"
796, "(fr)Very Good"
797, "(fr)Extremely fast with good weapons compatibility. Very useful in any kind of engagement."
798, "(fr)The PVN's Horus interceptor is the fastest ship in either the Terran or Vasudan arsenals, narrowly beating out the Terran Valkyrie. While both fast and agile, the Horus suffers from thin armor, and on paper should be at their most effective employing the same hit-and-run tactics as the slower Seth. However, they often mount Flail cannon, allowing them to split up enemy formations and tactically lock down enemy fighters with little chance of escape. For this reason, they are considered Class B combatants, and any in Hammer of Light hands should be treated as a serious threat."
799, "(fr)PVF Thot"
800, "(fr)Excellent fighter. Small and hard to hit, with speed and maneuverability to match. High rate of fire."
801, "(fr)The PVF Thot was intended to be the Vasudan equivalent of the Ulysses, and many of the same engineers worked on both designs. Unfortunately, the class was contracted to the Altair-based Sahr Corporation shortly before the fall of the Altair system to the Hammer of Light. Since then, the Thot has become nigh-synonymous with the HoL fighter corps, and the few Thots in PVN control are typically deployed for covert ops missions. Tactically, the Thot carries four primary cannon in a single bank, granting it a higher rate of fire than other fighter classes at the cost of technical inflexibility.<br/><br/>The Thot is considered a Class B combatant, bordering on Class A."
10509, "(fr)Advanced Vasudan heavy fighter. Massive missile bays and good primary firepower, but poor reactor recharge and durability for its class."
10510, "(fr)The PVF Tauret is a new type of assault fighter, weaving elements of the Hercules into conventional Vasudan fighter design. The Tauret features the same gun configuration as the Hercules, extensive missile racks reminiscent of the Athena, and the versatile suite of maneuvering thrusters common to Vasudan fighters. Its primary drawback is the extreme power draw these systems place on its reactor, which significantly limits the Tauret's endurance. Some dispute the Tauret's classification as an assault fighter, arguing that it more closely matches the Terran Apollo, and arguing for a new classification of 'space dominance' fighter instead. Either way, the Tauret's OpEval period was marked by the destruction of multiple HoL warships and convoys at their hands, and the GTA considers it a Class A combatant.<br/><br/>So far, the Tauret is produced exclusively by an offshoot of the Sahr Corporation in Alpha Centauri. Bizarrely, Alliance ambassadors to the PVE describe the Tauret as an 'apology' from Sahr for the loss of their headquarters to the Hammer of Light."
802, "(fr)PVB Osiris"
803, "(fr)Low maneuverability and speed. Carries a small number of bombs. Most commonly used in cruiser strikes."
804, "(fr)The Osiris is a medium bomber design not unlike our own Medusa. It has two forward gun mounts, though they not placed effectively for dogfighting, and primary defensive firepower is provided by a pair of turrets instead. While considerably less expensive than the venerable Amon, the Osiris is also considerably less capable and carries a significantly smaller payload. Some suspect politicking by the Akheton Corporation within the Vasudan Admiralty to be a factor in the Osiris' acceptance.<br/><br/>The Osiris is a Class B combatant, although even by bomber standards, its ability to threaten fighters is limited. The Hammer of Light have occasionally compensated for the Osiris' limited payload with kamikaze strikes."
805, "(fr)PVB Amon"
806, "(fr)Lowest maneuverability and extremely low top speed. Moving target, but the heaviest bomber in the PVN. Used against capital ships."
808, "(fr)The Amon is the heaviest bomber in the Parliamentary Vasudan Navy, comparable to the Terran Ursa. Where the Ursa is a new design, the Amon is an ancient one, kept relevant by an extensive series of block refits and upgrade packages on top of an incredibly potent base. Of the five Orion destroyers lost during the Fourteen Years War, three were destroyed by massed fire from Amon squadrons. Modern Amuns carry Terran Harbinger bombs instead of their original Vasudan ordnance, further increasing their killing power. While the Amon is protected by two turrets and heavy armor, it is even less maneuverable than the Ursa, but the PVN's attempt at a strike bomber, the Osiris, leaves much to be desired, sometimes forcing Amuns into battles they are ill-suited for.<br/><br/>As a fleet bomber, the Amon is considered a Class A combatant. While they are thankfully rare among the Hammer of Light, pilots in escort roles should prioritize them above all else."
809, "(fr)PVS Scarab"
810, "(fr)The Scarab support ship is a direct complement to the Terran Centaur. Like the Centaur, a small docking bay allows the Scarab to dock with battle-weary fighters to both refill their ordnance bays and repair any damaged subsystems they may have. In the years following the cease-fire, retrofit programs have allowed the Centaur to support Vasudan fighters and vice-verse. Further emphasizing the similarities between the two classes is their large blast radius when destroyed in action."
811, "(fr)PVT Isis"
812, "(fr)The PVT Isis is the PVN's primary military transport. Much like the Ma'at and Satis freighters, the Isis is well-armed for its class, with two turrets positioned to have wide firing arcs. The Isis' deadly reputation is enhanced by its small size. Lining up cannon fire while avoiding counterfire from the Isis' turrets is far harder than it would be against larger ships, and the Isis is often encountered in groups, which have numerous formations available to maximize turret coverage. What the Isis does have in common with the Elysium is its versatility. Isis transports, either singularly or in groups, are used as tugboats, repair craft, boarding transports, and occasionally as screening elements, with their turrets proving surprisingly effective at knocking out incoming bombs.<br/><br/>The Isis is considered a Class B combatant, but Hammer of Light Isis units should be assumed to contain boarding parties until proven otherwise."
813, "(fr)PVT Sesmu"
814, "(fr)The PVT Sesmu is a civilian transport with no military applications. Its Mekhu ME-14g powerplant makes the Sesmu fast for its size, but the ship's power grid is carefully optimized for speed, with only the barest concessions for point defenses. It also suffers from a lethargic subspace drive which can take up to 20 minutes to cold start, significantly limiting the Sesmu's ability to escape a fight. Nonetheless, the PVN does not have the same problems with piracy as the GTA does, and Sesmus are popular with logistics companies far from Hammer of Light territory, as well as diplomats, corporate executives, and others wishing to make a flashy impression.<br/><br/>The Sesmu is a Class E combatant, and it is less of a threat than an unsupported Watchdog sentry gun. Any encountered under Hammer of Light control are to be viewed with suspicion, however."
10511, "(fr)The PVT Qeb is a large Vasudan transport with cargo capacity exceeding some freighters. The Vasudan homeworld was a barren desert in a system tantalizingly full of resource-rich rocky worlds and asteroids. With the discovery of subspace travel, these resources became vastly more accessible. The unification of Vasudan society under a single parliamentary government, and the Akheton Corporation's favored status with that government, can both be tracked to Akheton's quick rollout of an inexpensive, modular, and highly reliable transport equally at home in deep space, atmosphere, and the newly discovered subspace environment. Hundreds of Qebs would come to ply trade lanes throughout the Vasuda system, and eventually others as well. All of these factors proved invaluable during the Shivan attack on Vasuda Prime, when the Vasudan Parliament invoked emergency powers to direct all available Qebs to evacuation efforts. This has given the Qeb a certain mystique among more spiritually inclined Vasudans, who see it as a bittersweet reminder of home."
815, "(fr)PVFr Ma'at"
816, "(fr)The Ma'at is the standard PVN military freighter. With three point defense turrets, Ma'at formations proved to be a thorny target for GTA fighters, directly inspiring the design of the Terran Poseidon freighter. Before the integration of Shivan shields into fighter designs, Ma'ats could effectively escort themselves, and even today, military surplus Ma'ats are a popular choice for Vasudan civilians on long-haul flights. Only the most brave and the most desperate pirate groups will try to engage them.<br/><br/>The Ma'at is considered a Class C combatant. Cargo ships operated by the Hammer of Light are always a valid target of opportunity, although pilots are encouraged to reinforce shields before engaging one."
817, "(fr)VAC 4"
818, "(fr)The VAC 4 cargo container is a significant refit of the VC 3. Heavily armored, comparable to the TAC 1 in Terran use, the VAC 4 is often used for carrying sensitive equipment, or supplies of value to the PVN. HoL VAC units should be destroyed whenever possible, ideally after collecting sensor scans, unless a capture operation has been authorized."
819, "(fr)PVFr Satis"
821, "(fr)The Satis freighter was originally misclassified as a gunship owing to its complement of five turrets and reinforced hull, and Satis tactics early in the War further confounded the issue. The PVN employed the Satis as a commerce raider, leveraging the PVE's then-superior understanding of subspace navigation to ambush and force the surrender of GTA cargo ships and hauling them off into subspace. With the increasing power of fighters on modern battlefields, the PVN has largely soured on the Satis, but still employs them as boarding craft. The Hammer of Light makes extensive use of the design as a gunship, capture ship, and cargo hauler.<br/><br/>The Satis is a Class C combatant, but any in HoL control should be approached with caution."
10512, "(fr)The Bast is a Vasudan civilian freighter. It is completely unarmed and lightly armored, and is completely defenseless in battle. Bast units are a common sight in the PVE core systems, which don't have the same problems with piracy as GTA systems tend to. This is actually a minor point of contention among Terrans, some of whom see the Bast and similar designs as emblematic of the PVE's $quoteunearned success$quote.<br/><br/>The Bast is, naturally, a Class F combatant. Rumors persist of Hammer of Light operatives among Bast crews, doing their jobs and quietly reporting back anything interesting they see."
823, "(fr)VC 3"
825, "(fr)The VC 3 is roughly comparable to, and the inspiration for, the Terran TC 2 container. The barren Vasudan homeworld benefited greatly from the import of offworld materials, and vast numbers of VC units were created to facilitate this process. Much like the TC 2, the VC 3 is fragile and entrusted only with low-priority supplies. One significant difference is the presence of a small station-keeping thruster assembly, which allows the VC 3 to be used low orbits without succumbing to atmospheric drag."
827, "(fr)PVFr Bes"
829, "(fr)The PVFr Bes is a newly commissioned bulk freighter, conceptually similar to the Terran Triton. Despite its unsightly appearance by Terran standards, its statistics excel on paper and it is remarkable as a freighter, able to load and unload cargo at a faster rate than any other freighter in existence. However, these freighters are underwhelming in terms of armament, costly, and more vulnerable than the Ma'at freighter. Their continued production is evidence that the PVE is willing to accept these costs, believing the benefits of the design significantly outweigh them."
831, "(fr)VAC 5"
833, "(fr)The Vasudan VAC 5 is a next-generation armored cargo container that is used to transport fragile or valuable equipment to front-line bases. These containers are better protected than most combat spacecraft, giving their cargoes an excellent chance to survive collisions and stray energy blasts. With the Ma'at and Satis likely to remain in service for the foreseeable future, the VAC 5 will only supplement, not replace the VAC 4."
835, "(fr)PVSC Imhotep"
837, "(fr)The PVSC Imhotep is the standard Vasudan research vessel. Similar to the Faustus, the Imhotep is capable of filling a variety of different scientific roles, from on-board research to conducting sensor surveys. One major difference between the two designs is the Imhotep's pod bay, intended to carry four remote research pods to augment the ship's on-board sensor systems. The Hammer of Light, however, typically employs the Imhotep as an electronics warfare vessel, and these ships are sometimes seen hijacking commercial broadcasts and replacing them with propaganda espousing the HoL's ideology."
839, "(fr)PVC Aten"
840, "(fr)The Aten is a strike cruiser design developed during the Terran-Vasudan War. Atens are most directly comparable to the GTC Fenris, although they are even less durable than their Terran counterpart. Compared to the dreaded PVC Mekhet, the Aten offers significantly enhanced maneuverability and acceleration, but lacks the heavy ship-to-ship turrets that gave the Mekhet its bite. The Aten is much more cost-effective, however, and formations of Atens proved themselves much more flexible at answering Fenris deployments than the handful of available Mekhets, leading to the Aten becoming the PVN's standard cruiser. Unfortunately, the Hammer of Light was able to capture several early in the uprising, and continue to manufacture more at the captured Sahr shipyards in Altair.<br/><br/>Like the Fenris, the Aten is considered a Class C combatant."
841, "(fr)PVC Mekhet"
842, "(fr)The Mekhet is an older Vasudan heavy cruiser. Heavily armored, and armed with two ship-to-ship turrets, three light missile stations, and seven point defense turrets, the Mekhet was a terrifying force in the early stages of the Fourteen Years War. Mekhet deployments at key border positions prevented the GTA from effectively launching attacks into Vasudan territory. The development of the GTC Fenris shifted the balance, with Fenris groups demonstrating strategic flexibility which a single Mekhet couldn't effectively answer, and the later introduction of the Leviathan provided the GTA with a tactical answer to the Mekhet as well. During the GTA's first offensive into the Antarès system, the Battle of Gulnara saw numerous Mekhets outmaneuvered and destroyed. Since then, Mekhet production has entirely ceased, with the few remaining units held in reserve at key jump nodes and strategically vital installations.<br/><br/>The Mekhet is a Class B combatant. If any are encountered under Hammer of Light control, they must be reported immediately, and destroyed if possible."
843, "(fr)PVD Typhon"
844, "(fr)The Typhon destroyer is the Vasudan equivalent of the Terran Orion, and every bit as deadly. The class was first engaged in the Vega system, where it destroyed the GTD Eisenhower and most of 4th Fleet before withdrawing with minimal damage. The Typhon was initially believed to be a unique ship, and the discovery of multiple Typhon-class destroyers forced an immediate reorganization of the entire GTA fleet to contain the threat. It was eventually discovered that the Typhon's turrets, while powerful, are relatively fragile and vulnerable to coordinated bomber strikes, but the Typhon's point defenses and fighter squadrons make this a tricky weakness to exploit. In the postwar period, all Typhons in the PVN have been retrofitted with Aratrum torpedo stations, granting them even more offensive firepower.<br/><br/>Like the Orion, the Typhon is considered a Class S combatant. Very few Typhons have been lost in battle, but several have defected to or been captured by the Hammer of Light. We believe that the HoL has trouble supplying these ships on long campaigns, limiting their offensive capabilities."
10513, "(fr)PVI Nagada Outpost"
10514, "(fr)Nagada Outpost was once an unremarkable asteroid in Sirius. During the Fourteen Years War, the PVN constructed a low-visibility outpost inside the asteroid, providing a supply point for fleets trying to punch through to Regulus. The Shivan Incursion saw Nagada's mission flipped on its head, as Nagada became a safe zone for ships, Terran and Vasudan alike, fleeing Shivan and Hammer activities. After the war, the station was finally decommissioned at the request of Sirius' government."
845, "(fr)Array"
10515, "(fr)PVI Cairo"
10516, "(fr)The Shivan Incursion demonstrated just how vulnerable immobile installations could be to enemy attack. The PVN took these harsh lessons to heart and developed the Cairo as a frontline military installation. The Cairo could be considered roughly equivalent to the Terran Arcadia, but possesses far superior armament. Analysts predict that an unsupported Cairo could narrowly defeat most currently serving vessels, and Shivan destroyers as well. Factoring in the numerous wings of fighters and bombers contained within its bays, and the Cairo is rightly seen as one of the most formidable PVN assets, a focus of power among the stars."
846, "(fr)PVI Abydos"
847, "(fr)The Abydos is a small Vasudan installation modeled after the much larger Karnak class. Where the Karnak is a fully functional deep-space habitat, however, the Abydos is little more than a defensive artillery piece. Since Abydos units cannot be repositioned in response to jump node shifts, they are not employed in blockades, and are typically seen flanking key pieces of orbital infrastructure."
848, "(fr)PVI Djoser"
849, "(fr)The Djoser serves a similar role for Vasudans to the Terran Ganymede, although differences in fleet philosophy lead to a radically different design. The PVE is much more comfortable than the GTA upgrading and retrofitting older ships, and the Djoser is oriented more towards repairs and upgrades than on construction. It is competent in both roles, however, and a suite of five Djoser rings provide the core construction capabilities of the Hammer of Light shipyards in Altair."
850, "(fr)PVSG Ankh"
851, "(fr)The Ankh is a Vasudan sentry gun. On paper, it is comparable to the Terran Watchdog. In practice, the philosophy behind the two weapons is very different. While the GTA expects its sentries to be semi-autonomous, leading to the Cerberus upgrade package, the PVN deploys the Ankh primarily as a supplemental weapon to shore up defenses at existing installations. Pressure from the GTA Admiralty has lead to the development of the PVSG Edjo $quotenext generation$quote sentry, but, since its only noteworthy feature is low price, it seems that the PVN has little interest in small-scale static defenses."
853, "(fr)PVEP Ra"
854, "(fr)The Ra escape pod has been the standard emergency vehicle on Vasudan capital ships since the Terran-Vasudan War. While larger than the Terran Hermès, the Ra actually has lower passenger capacity. This is partially a consequence of Vasudan physiology, but also of differences in military philosophy. A significant portion of the Ra's internal volume is intended for storing equipment and records which could be of use to the larger war effort, and the craft's homing beacon is more highly rated than its life support. While this attitude may seem callous by GTA standards, PVN ships do nonetheless maintain enough escape pods for a full crew evacuation should one be called for."
10517, "(fr)VM Contusus"
10518, "(fr)The Contusus is a Hammer of Light-designed mine based on the Terran Arothron. The Contusus lacks the Arothron's decoy beacon, but instead mounts heavier ordnance and a small maneuvering thruster suite."
855, "(fr)HLB Hésat"
856, "(fr)Maneuverable bomber. Frail and has low ordnance capacity."
857, "(fr)The Hésat appears to be a product of Sahr Corporation's Altair shipyards, currently under Hammer of Light control. Manufactured in unexpectedly large quantities, these bombers appear to be designed as cost-effective supplements to the Osiris, Amon, and Sekhmet, able to be used in swarm situations. While individual Hésats have limited ordnance capacity, they have enough maneuverability to avoid counterfire and deliver that ordnance very effectively. It is possible that the Hammer of Light took inspiration for the Hésat from the GTB Zeus strike bomber.<br/><br/>Hésats are considered Class B combatants. They are a serious threat to cruisers and cargo haulers, but should be given a lower target priority while escorting capital ships."
858, "(fr)HLB Sekhmet"
860, "(fr)Vasudan-Shivan hybrid. Fast and powerful."
861, "(fr)The Sekhmet is a Hammer of Light design that appears to be a fusion of Vasudan and Shivan technology. The HoL claims its design was adapted from a new class of Shivan bomber not yet encountered by the GTA or PVN. With high speed and maneuverability, the Sekhmet boasts Shivan-like flight characteristics, but it is also highly durable and carries anti-capital torpedoes like a heavy bomber. Analysis of Sekhmet debris lends considerable support to the HoL's claims of successfully hybridizing Vasudan and Shivan systems.<br/><br/>The Sekhmet is the only strikecraft the Alliance has ever considered a Class S combatant. Destroy on sight."
862, "(fr)HLC Newet"
863, "(fr)Small and heavily armed, the Newet blurs the line between a cruiser and a gunship. A single Newet prototype was produced at the Sahr shipyards before their fall to the Hammer of Light, who modified the design for their needs. The Newet carries an incredible sixteen turrets, one carrying the same heavy cannon as the old PVC Mekhet, the others optimized for swatting away fighters. Pilots attacking a Newet are encouraged to focus fire on its turrets so as to limit its counterfire as much as possible.<br/><br/>The Newet is a Class A combatant, although held back by limited durability. Some analysts believe the Newet's power grid may use Shivan components to power its weapon systems."
864, "(fr)HLC Selket"
865, "(fr)As enigmatic as it is deadly, the Selket is a cruiser of Hammer of Light design. With durability approaching that of a Shivan Lilith and comparable firepower, the Selket is a significant threat to all current Terran and Vasudan cruiser classes. Given what has been observed of the HLB Sekhmet, Allied analysists fear the Selket may also include Shivan hybrid systems. Fortunately, very few have ever been encountered, and the ship may even be unique.<br/><br/>The Selket is a Class A threat."
10519, "(fr)Power Node"
10520, "(fr)HLC Selket Refit"
10521, "(fr)At least one Selket cruiser, the HLC Taouret, has done extensive refitting, granting it exotic capabilities above what have been previously encountered. The refit includes a small fighterbay, making it the second-smallest ship to have one after Canberra. It also features an exotic form of FTL technology, allowing it to 'disappear' and reappear interstellar distances away without the use of a jump node. It is speculated that these two capabilities explain how the Hammer of Light forces in Luyten remain well-supplied in spite of the ongoing ADEIS blockade."
10522, "(fr)HLI Khaiou"
10523, "(fr)The Khaiou installation was originally commissioned by the PVN as a low-visibility special operations post. Built into the surface of a large asteroid, the Khaiou provided PVN hunter-killer teams in Alpha Centauri with a discreet point to strike from and retreat to. The success of these tactics lead to the establishment of a similar base in Sirius, at which point Khaiou Station fell into disuse. Eventually, the Hammer of Light secretly reactivated Khaiou and used it as a supply station for their own espionage service. It remained in use for some time before its docking bay was destroyed during the recovery of a Vasudan Intelligence officer, leading the Hammer to abandon the station once again. Khaiou's reactor was subsequently detonated to ensure it could not be reactivated, bringing an ignoble end to its convoluted history."
10525, "(fr)The International Atmospheric And Space Administration's Fadlan was the first subspace-capable vessel produced by humanity - to an extent. The vessel employed a then-novel propulsion system called a 'convergence engine', a precursor to modern jump drives. After its maiden flight proved the viability of subspace travel, the Fadlan was employed as a logistical support vessel for the Jupiter colony, ferrying supplies and personnel to the settlement far faster than conventional haulers could. The Fadlan was eventually lost with all hands when a power grid failure left it stranded in subspace, and its loss is cited as a major contributing factor in the Jovian declaration of independence."
866, "(fr)TF Angel"
867, "(fr)Obsolete interceptor design. Low offensive capability but effective maneuverability and speed."
868, "(fr)Introduced shortly after the formation of the GTA, the Angel scout fighter holds a special place in Terran history as the first spacecraft ever contracted by the Galactic Terran Alliance. It also holds the dubious distinction of introducing Han-Ronald's near-monopoly in GTA fighter spaceframes. At the opening of the Fourteen Years War, the Angel was well-regarded for its ability to scout out and harass PVN positions, but the introduction of the Seth quickly changed the dynamic. While the Angel's legacy lives on as the template for the Valkyrie interceptor, and a few Angel spaceframes have been transferred to customs duty, the vast majority are operated by civilian security contractors and the occasional well-funded pirate group.<br/><br/>The Angel is considered a Class D combatant, much like the PVF Anubis."
869, "(fr)TF Pie"
10526, "(fr)Obsolete light fighter. Has capable primary firepower but no missile capacity."
871, "(fr)The Pie is an old light fighter which was in service even before the Unification War, and its manufacturer, the now defunct Trenton Industries, happily sold Pie units to multiple sides simultaneously. Pies are maneuverable even by modern standards, but are entirely incapable of carrying missiles, vastly limiting their effectiveness on modern battlefields. As private security goes, the Pie is considered a budget option, and their operators have a somewhat deserved reputation for taking contracts from anyone, regardless of legality.<br/><br/>The Pie is a Class E combatant, but can be effective with numerical superiority."
872, "(fr)TF Mustang Alpha"
10527, "(fr)Obsolete space superiority fighter. Still maneuverable and decently armed, but fragile with small ordnance capacity."
873, "(fr)The Mustang Alpha was a workhorse fighter throughout the Unification War, and narrowly missed being adopted as the Galactic Terran Alliance's primary fighter after unification. Highly versatile, the Mustang's design philosophies would ultimately lay the foundation for the design of the GTF Apollo. It also benefited from a highly adaptable spaceframe, and Mustang Alpha assembly lines could be quickly retooled to produce Mustang Bêta fighter-bombers and Mustang Charlie electronics warfare ships as needed. The Mustang Alpha is still the baseline civilian craft, and limited production continues in systems where demand for private security is high.<br/><br/>Mustang Alphas are considered a Class D combatant, edging on Class C."
874, "(fr)TF Mustang Alpha Block 276a"
10528, "(fr)Unique craft. Far better than it would appear to be."
875, "(fr)Mustang Alpha serial number A-G259 was used by Northrop-Grumman as a testbed for emergent technologies. It was reportedly wrecked during a test of the Block 276a upgrade package and auctioned off for scrap. It was purchased by the Regulus-based Kresge Connections and reportedly broken up, only to reappear six months later in Antarès, operated by none other than notorious pirate Arris Gavel. Gavel has publicly stated that he arranged for the recovery of the upgrade package and installed it on his existing Mustang Alpha, and while it is widely assumed his statement is a lie to cover for contacts at Kresge, no definitive evidence has turned up either way. The rebuilt A-G259 is considered a Class C combatant and a serious threat to regional stability, much like Gavel himself."
876, "(fr)TF Ion"
10529, "(fr)Obsolete shuttlecraft with minor combat capabilities."
877, "(fr)The Ion was originally used as $quotetactical transport$quote during the Unification War. Little more than a shuttle with a small number of weapon hardpoints, the Ion was intended to contribute to its own escort. While it was able to defend itself adequately from the low-tech fighters of the time, the Ion has become woefully out of date. Surviving units see limited use as cargo handlers at dockyards and little else."
10530, "(fr)Like the lighter Pie, the Falcon spaceframe dates back to the Unification War, where it saw service with multiple opposed factions. Slow and ungainly, the Falcon was effective in exactly one role: delivering massive numbers of high-yield unguided rockets to enemy warships, and occasionally surviving thanks to oversized armor plates. Early in the Fourteen Years War, the Falcon developed an unexpected popularity among security firms, since it could effectively ward off the freighters used by the PVN's then-common ambush-and-abduct tactics. So long as the Hammer of Light remains a credible threat, Falcons will continue to have a role in civilian shipping - which is unfortunate, since the GTA would rather declare them prohibited to cut off pirate groups' supplies of replacement parts.<br/><br/>The Falcon is a Class D combatant."
10531, "(fr)The Kestrel originated with the People's Republic of Mars, one of the power blocs eventually subsumed into the Galactic Terran Alliance during the Unification War. Developed by the precursors of the Han-Ronald Corporation at the request of the Martian government, the Kestrel is even heavier than the Falcon fielded by other early factions. Much like the Falcon, the Kestrel has remained relevant long after the Unification War as a private security asset.<br/><br/>The Kestrel is a Class D combatant."
10532, "(fr)The Electron is an unusual craft developed by the Gerace Corporation for sale to mining corporations, for whom it fulfills two distinct roles. First, it operates as an escort fighter to ward off pirate threats. Secondly, it can be reconfigured as a mining scout, swapping its secondary ordnance for a suite of asteroid survey equipment. This bimodal design has proved popular enough for Gerace to maintain it as a core product after sales of the Proton transport and Ion shuttle have dwindled. It is an especially common sight amongst STX Exploration operations in the Frontière systems of Laramis and Luyten."
10533, "(fr)The Hauméa is a rare class of bomber designed and constructed by the paramilitary Second Dawn Society. While such heavy ordnance in civilian hands would be highly illegal in Galactic Terran space, the Hauméa was officially greenlit by the Luyten New Alliance in exchange for SDA cooperation in policing the system's Oort Cloud. Hauméas sometimes accompany Pélé patrols when encounters with Hammer of Light warships are expected.<br/><br/>The Hauméa is roughly comparable to the GTB Zeus. It is less maneuverable but slightly faster, and sacrifices ordnance capacity for armor. The Hauméa's most unique feature its offset triple-gun rack, which is typically loaded with an anti-hull cannon for supplementary firepower. The surprising success of this design against Hammer of Light assets in Luyten has attracted the attention of GTA observers.<br/><br/>A squadron of Hauméas was assigned to supplement Amanu Station's air wing shortly after the Society's entry into the ADEIS conflict."
879, "(fr)TB Mustang Bêta"
10534, "(fr)Obsolete fighter-bomber. Low ordnance capacity and firepower, but is relatively maneuverable."
880, "(fr)The Mustang Bêta is a fighter-bomber variant of the Mustang Alpha. During the Unification War, it effectively balanced maneuverability and self-defense with anti-warship firepower, but it has become outdated on modern battlefields. While the Mustang Alpha is a common sight among security contractors, the Bêta variant is prohibited to civilian operators. Pirate groups have been known to load them out as heavy missile boats to suppress their targets' escorts.<br/><br/>The GTA sets a minimum threshold for bombers as Class C combatants. Treat it as such."
881, "(fr)TGs Protubérance"
10535, "(fr)Gunship"
882, "(fr)The Protubérance was first introduced as a mining ship shortly after the Unification War. The turbulent unification period left lots of room for pirates to hide, so the Protubérance was loaded for bear, with point defenses and light railguns to drive off aggression on the Frontière. Many of these ships, their mining days long behind them, have been retrofitted by system militias and security contractors, while others have themselves gone pirate. Pirate Protubérances are especially problematic for civilian security, and typically require a military response to hunt down - an ironic fate given the class's original purpose."
883, "(fr)Radar Array"
10536, "(fr)Megiddo Station is the headquarters of the ultra-survivalist Second Dawn Society, who intend to create a self-sustaining bastion that can outlast a second Shivan incursion. Until very recently, almost nothing was known about the station, in keeping with the SDA's erstwhile policy of enforced self-sufficiency by secrecy. The station was discovered during a joint rescue operation by the 508th Loaded Dice and Luyten New Alliance forces.<br/><br/>Megiddo Station is built into a large Oort Cloud object with a highly eccentric orbit. The station has a minimal amount of superstructure on the surface of the asteroid, but protects itself from long-range sensors by keeping the majority of the structure buried inside. The interior of the station is highly utilitarian, with a majority of the usable area taken up by workshops, warehouses, and life support systems. Megiddo also hosts the majority of the Second Dawn Society's well-equipped fighter corps."
10537, "(fr)Thyatira Station is one of the Second Dawn Society's asteroid facilities. In the long term, the SDA intends for Thyatira to become a redundancy for Megiddo Station, giving the organization a fallback should Shivan forces detect and destroy Megiddo. At present, construction on the station has barely begun, although the SDA has indicated a willingness to host civilian refuges in its partially-complete habitation wing."
10538, "(fr)Sardis Station is a highly unusual station operated by the Second Dawn Society. The station is built into a naturally hollow Oort Cloud object, and the SDA have put its massive inner chamber to a creative, albeit dangerous, use. A partially complete ship, the O-Inari, rests in Sardis' core. When complete, this ship will have the ability to jump from inside the station deep into UV Ceti's gravity well, deploy and retrieve portable antimatter condensers, and jump back to the station's interior, with the asteroid's bulk acting as a natural baffle to Shivan sensors. Should the Shivans return, this plan will provide the SDA with a reliable source of power so long as they can perform the extremely precise navigational calculations needed for the return journey."
10539, "(fr)Ephesos Station is described by the Second Dawn Society as an 'arsenal station'. Like other SDA installations, the majority of the station's structure is inside a large Oort Cloud object. Most of the asteroid's internal volume has been converted into a dizzying array of drone hangars, capable of housing and deploying Pèlerin and Elepaio sensor probes, Phidias and Hégéia utility drones, and even Amazon Advanced training drones modified as subspace-capable carriers for smaller drone types. Ephesos' primary role in a Shivan survival scenario will be to discreetly monitor their movements with its probes, allowing the SDA to coordinate efforts and remain undetected. For now, Ephesos is primarily employed as a construction depot, using its drones to set up infrastructure and booby traps throughout the Oort Cloud. The 'arsenal' in 'arsenal station' comes from a stock of explosive-laden Amazons being developed as crude subspace-capable torpedoes, which were unfortunately confiscated by the Hammer of Light during their occupancy of Megiddo Station."
10540, "(fr)TSG Tyrving"
10541, "(fr)The Tyrving defense platform was developed during the Fourteen Years War to check aggression by Vasudan capital ships. Featuring six high velocity 430mm fusion mortars backed up by sophisticated self-repair systems, the Tyrving could serve as a fully automated anti-capital ship sentry gun, although regulations required them to be overseen by human operators. Tyrvings served in frontline positions until the introduction of the Typhon-class destroyer, which it could not effectively engage. Even before then, the Tyrving's large size and lack of point defenses had proven themselves to be a liability. Some Tyrving platforms were reactivated during the Shivan Incursion, where they provided a short-term but effective deterrent which bought time for the Allied response to mobilize. No Tyrving platforms remain in GTA service as a result of their inherent tactical flaws, but some remain active in Frontière systems under the control of authorized militia groups."
884, "(fr)TM Arothron"
886, "(fr)The Arothron mine couples a subspace decoy beacon with multi-missile countermeasure packages. Arothrons were employed to considerable effect during the Fourteen Years War, but have become less useful as subspace navigation technology improves. A detonating Arothron releases dozens of missiles in dense swarms, a potentially fatal ambush for any ship caught near one. The mines can be configured to detonate automatically, raising concerns about their actual legality. Worryingly, Arothron units are occasionally spotted in pirate hands."
10542, "(fr)Armed with the Antarès Federation's new flak weaponry, the Garm is designed to take down enemy strikecraft, serving as an all-purpose patrol craft for Federation-controlled territories. Analysts believe the Garm is a very radical redesign of the Leviathan cruiser, developed by former Han-Ronald employees commissioned by the Federation. The Garm is mainly deployed as an escort for convoys, but the Federation is known to run offensive anti-fighter drills as well."
10543, "(fr)Very Light"
10544, "(fr)Converted racing ship. Fragile hull but advanced avionics."
10545, "(fr)The Týr began life as a civilian racing ship, the Saab Huracan. The design faded into obscurity in the wartime economy of the Shivan Incursion, until the Treaty of Luyten brought it back. The independence-minded Luyten New Alliance selected the Huracan as the basis of a native fighter, designated 'Týr' after the Germanic deity. Týr production in Luyten has ramped up quickly on political grounds, and GTA analysts cite the LNA's over-reliance on a single fighter class as a contributing factor to their activation of the treaty's Mutual Defense clause.<br/><br/>Tactically, the Týr occupies a niche somewhere between pure intercept and space superiority. The ship's weapon emplacements have been integrated into the underside of the hull, right along the ship's centerline, and offer moderate compatibility and high accuracy. The ship's non-weapon avionics are considerably more noteworthy. A distributed sensor network embedded in the ship's hull allows it to resolve sensor traces with higher resolution than any comparable fighter, and prototypical 'sprint' jump drives enhance the ship's subspace agility. In keeping with LNA philosophy, these systems allow the Týr to double as a customs boat or survey ship, and the cockpit even integrates a second seat for a technical observer. The LNA has expressed an interest in exporting the class in these roles.<br/><br/>LNA pilots sometimes accent their ships with custom paint jobs. These decorations are strictly personal, and do not denote rank or squadron affiliation. The Týr has not been issued a combatant classification by the GTA, but is generally held to be a Class C or Class B combatant."
10546, "(fr)In the aftermath of the Great War, Triton Dynamics proposed the Schrodinger as a more defensible competitor to the venerable - and vulnerable - Faustus-class science cruiser. While the design showed promise, GTA doctrine already called for auxiliary ships to be kept far from the front lines whenever possible, and civilian interests balked at the per-unit cost. The Schrodinger finally found a buyer in the Frontière environment of Luyten, where three of the ships form the backbone of the Luyten New Alliance's communications network, and others serve in various research capacities."
10547, "(fr)The Maiman class, innocuously named after the Terran inventor of the laser, is the only dedicated weapons platform in the Luyten New Alliance fleet. The class was designed from the ground up to support a prototypical photon beam cannon under development by LNA researchers. The ships are therefore highly valuable, and their protection must be a top priority at all times. The Maiman project is a double-edged sword for the Luyten government. While it represents a valuable bargaining chip, it has also brought to light internal tensions regarding the proper role of weapons development in the LNA movement.<br/><br/>Individual Maimans differ widely in their capabilities. The lead ship of the class (originally the Vredefort, since re-designated Shannon) exposed flaws in the design's power grid, and now serves as an auxiliary communications hub. Its successor, the Chicxulub, corrected these issues at the expense of an anemic ETS system. Later ships are expected to address this issue.<br/><br/>The LNA classifies the Maiman as a 'cutter', but it is functionally a heavy cruiser. GTA personnel are nonetheless to use the LNA's designation to avoid a diplomatic incident. Beam-capable Maimans are considered Class A combatants, while the Shannon is considered a Class D combatant."
10548, "(fr)The Magellan-class explorer was originally designed as a subspace-capable habitat. Designed in the late 23rd century, these modular colony vessels facilitated the emigration of millions from the Sol System to the Terran colonies in previously unseen comfort and security. While historically significant, the Magellan began to diminish in significance with the establishment of planetary colonies, and most were eventually mothballed. In GTA space, the vessel's role has since been filled by dedicated ships like the Faustus, Bromios, and Florence. In Luyten, however, the concept of an independent habitat has found new resonance. The Luyten New Alliance has resurrected over a dozen Magellans, which serve as both housing and offices for entire research projects.<br/><br/>The Magellan class is durable, but unarmed, and as such is a Class F combatant. LNA Magellans often mount exotic defenses such as sensor scramblers and sprint jump drives."
10549, "(fr)The capital of the Luyten New Alliance, Amanu Station is home to both the LNA government and dozens of civilian enterprises that have staked out a claim in the wild Frontière. Built almost organically around the frame of the largest colony vessel in LNA possession, Amanu is both a philosophical reflection of the LNA's utopian ideals, and a practical nod to the lack of habitable planets in the system. While the station rivals an Orion-class destroyer in scale, it carries no turrets of its own, relying instead on its oversized air wing - an estimated eighty Týr-class interceptors - and Dainsleif-class heavy sentries for defense. The station integrates with the system's network of communication hubs and science cruisers, allowing very fast fighter response to developments throughout the system. The LNA posits that Amanu's strategic capabilities are sufficient to stop enemy incursion during the buildup phase. This claim is generally regarded as dubious, and will largely depend on the development of LNA bomber classes or the success of the Maiman project."
10550, "(fr)The Dainsleif is an oversized sentry gun, drawing inspiration from the outmoded Patriot-class defense node and recent developments in flak systems. In a radical challenge to conventional sentry gun design, it is heavily armed, heavily armored, and not intended for clustered deployments. Several of these platforms contribute to the defense of Amanu Station, and others guard key navigational sites throughout the system."
10551, "(fr)Part of an effort to contact Sol using high-intensity radio pulses."
887, "(fr)TDr Phidias"
888, "(fr)The Phidias service drone is the latest in a long line of construction vehicles that can trace its lineage back to before the GTA, and, arguably, to before the advent of subspace travel. At the time, human spacecraft were assembled on Earth, which had well-established infrastructure for that purpose. The nascent Martian colony, wishing to decrease its reliance on the homeworld and lacking such infrastructure, partnered with the Han-Ronald Corporation to produce a series of orbital construction vehicles, allowing them to jump-start their own construction efforts. Once the technology was proven, it was quickly imported by IASA administrators back on Earth, although economic and technological inertia kept planet-side shipyards in operation for a long time as well. These primitive OCVs typically had an onboard pilot, and it wasn't until the colonization of Jupiter that autonomous variants truly came into vogue.<br/><br/>While Han-Ronald owes much of its early success to the orbital construction vehicle concept, the OCV concept itself owes its success to a quirk of contemporary law, which allowed corporations on Earth and Luna to reproduce the original design. This lead to a rapid ramp-up of competing designs, some of them quite exotic, which ultimately yielded a handful of highly optimized OCV types. As part of its post-Unification War economic recovery programs, the GTA standardized these designs, with the most common, a highly mobile core equipped with a manipulator arm and hardpoints for hot-swappable equipment, being designated the Phidias. Phidias-type drones are now produced by a wide range of corporations, all of whom bring their own innovations to the basic Phidias specification, and Phidias variants are employed in an equally wide range of tasks by both GTA and civilian interests. The design has even seen some limited success in Vasudan shipyards."
890, "(fr)TDr 3301"
891, "(fr)Derived from the noted Elepaio drone, itself a derivative of the now ancient Firebee training drone, the 3301 repair drone was designed as an additional money-maker and the first real challenger to the Phidias drone on the greater civilian market. While the target market of the Phidias is outpost and large ship construction, the 3301 was targeted more towards fighter, transport, and freighter repair. Significantly cheaper than the Phidias both to purchase and operate, the 3301's systems are comparatively basic and far less capable than the Phidias at repair work. Budget consumers have used the 3301, typically in concert with Terran workers, to provide maintenance services in mining and research facilities with lower profit margins that could not afford a full Phidias fleet. This low cost has allowed the 3301 to take a double digit share of the market, though the Phidias still controls the majority."
893, "(fr)TT Proton"
894, "(fr)Gerace's Proton-class transport is a lighter design favored by the Terran upper class for its eye-catching style. It is well armored but mostly defenseless, reliant on the security of a system or escorting fighters to protect it from even a lone interceptor. Common users of these transports include CEOs of important companies, celebrities, politicians, scientists and academics, and wealthy socialites. In the troubled Regulus system, however, they are strongly associated with crime bosses of the Regulus Syndicate, and generally treated with extreme caution."
895, "(fr)TT Cretheus"
896, "(fr)The Cretheus medium transport is a newer civilian design primarily used to move large numbers of emigrating civilians to Frontière systems on the borders of the GTA. While capable of carrying many passengers, the Cretheus possesses the most spartan of accommodations to maximize its occupancy limit. Critics of the design argue that the transport is more hazardous to ride as a passenger in than smaller ships like the Elysium, but proponents consider the ship's speed a boon, letting it get away from convoy raids more reliably than any other competing transports in its class. Official Alliance policy is that the argument is a moot point, since neither type of craft should operate without escort."
10552, "(fr)Courier"
10553, "(fr)Fast intersystem courier. Well-defended for a ship of its type."
10554, "(fr)The Wyverne is a long-range fast courier, designed to rapidly ferry personnel and light cargo across many systems. To that end, it mounts three point defense stations and powerful maneuvering thrusters, allowing it to tangle with pirate forces if needed. Unfortunately, these same characteristics make it desirable by those same pirates, for whom it is a valuable, albeit rare, option for capture operations."
10555, "(fr)Clamp"
10556, "(fr)TC EC7"
10557, "(fr)External cargo pod for the Wyverne courier."
10558, "(fr)The largest and the most heavily armored cargo used by Terran ships, TAC 7 units are a rare sight, typically use for the long-term storage of dangerous goods."
10559, "(fr)A large fluid container, TCL 1 units are a rare sight, typically use for the long-term storage of dangerous liquids and gasses."
897, "(fr)TFr Albanus"
898, "(fr)The Albanus is an old civilian freighter design. Subach-Innes originally devised the Albanus as a utility craft for planetary colonization efforts. To this end, the Albanus is atmosphere-capable and mounts massive VTOL engines for planetary landings, and its primary cargo container, the TC-ALB, is rated for human habitation, allowing it to ferry colonists and livestock to their new home. Only the much newer government-commissioned TC-TRI shares this characteristic. Unfortunately for the Albanus, human society was about to fly into nearly two decades of war. As planetary colonization efforts fell to zero, Subach-Innes was left with an inventory of Albanus prototypes and no market for them. The Albanus' excellent ability to maneuver in atmosphere allowed it to find a niche market as a gas giant surveyor, but it was the container's ability to carry human beings that ended up being the Albanus' saving grace, as the governments of Sirius and Antarès expressed interest in the Albanus as a prison transport. Unfortunately for Subach-Innes, these same contracts ensure they will be stuck manufacturing replacement parts for the foreseeable future.<br/><br/>The idea of a Marine transport variant of the Albanus, carrying independently mobile boarding pods instead of its standard containers, was briefly popular among the Admiralty. Designated the GTT Rathaeshtar, the concept fell out of vogue after repeated failures to effect clean pod separation under simulated battle conditions, although the prototype has not been formally decommissioned."
899, "(fr)TC-ALB"
900, "(fr)The TC-ALB is the container used by the Albanus freighter. Originally designed to carry colonists and livestock, the TC-ALB holds the record for sheer quantity of safety certifications - and the highest price of any container besides the massive TC-TRI. The TC-RAE is a proposed variant equipped with thrusters and breeching charges, intended to deliver Marines to boarding actions more safely than a standard transport."
901, "(fr)TC A09"
902, "(fr)The A09 cargo container is an old civilian cargo unit. Its simple-yet-durable construction allows it to fulfill nearly all freight transportation and storage duties for any type of cargo."
903, "(fr)TC A17t"
904, "(fr)A17 containers are an upgraded variant of the old A09 unit. Boasting reinforced armor and superior environmental controls, these containers offer better protection for important materials."
905, "(fr)TFr Atlantis"
906, "(fr)The Atlantis is a large freighter design, originally developed by Subach-Innes for colonization missions. It was meant to partner with the Albanus, carrying the cargo and equipment needed to seed a new colony while the Albanus carried the people. After being unloaded, the Atlantis would remain in orbit to act as a comms relay. Unlike the Albanus, the Atlantis' simple design - little more than a network of docking struts attached to large engine pods - had no trouble finding buyers in other markets. Beyond the obvious bulk hauling missions, Atlantis spaceframes have found use in scientific survey missions, where they can carry hundreds of probes to an area of interest.<br/><br/>The GTA Internal Ministry almost commissioned a variant of the Atlantis, which would have been called the GTFr Damysus, but ended up selecting the Navy-commissioned Triton to simplify appropriations."
907, "(fr)TAC 1-ILS-B"
908, "(fr)The Integrated Launch System, or ILS, is a block modification for the venerable TAC 1 container. The modification mounts an external door at one or both ends of the container, and runs an internal cargo elevator along the container's spine, allowing stored objects to be launched automatically. While the system was originally designed to deploy scientific survey probes, it has largely been co-opted by criminal elements, who use it to deploy mines and sentry guns, or even as an improvised hangar for Pie and Angel-class fighters. GTA pilots are encouraged to treat ILS-capable containers of unknown ownership as potential popup threats."
909, "(fr)TAC 1-ILS-A"
910, "(fr)TGas-1"
911, "(fr)The TGas-1 is the basic Terran cargo container for carrying large quantities of gases or liquids."
912, "(fr)TG Bromios"
913, "(fr)The Bromios has functioned as a Terran gas miner since before the Unification War. A simple, rugged, and reliable craft, the Bromios is designed to collect and process the gases found in the atmospheres of gas giant planets. Gas from these atmospheres are broken down into their constituent elements on board the Bromios' internal facilities, extracting whatever hydrogen and helium can be removed from the gases. These are then pumped into refinery facilities where they are processed to isolate the necessary deuterium and tritium used as fuel for the reactors in Terran military and civilian ships. While a critical asset to all of humanity, the Bromios is large, slow, bulky, and poorly armed, making it a prize target for pirates."
914, "(fr)Collector"
915, "(fr)TCa Canberra"
10560, "(fr)Transport/Carrier"
916, "(fr)The Canberra specifications were developed and published, pro bono, by the Mesa Corporation early in the Shivan Incursion. The intention was to provide a mobile rally point for private security and militia forces, who were frequently called upon to respond to Shivan aggression in areas where GTA fighter cover was spotty. The Canberra provides a small hangar, decent armor and maneuverability, and four missile hardpoints - originally designed with Mesa's Interceptor missile in mind. With the Mesa Corporation leading the effort, many Canberra platforms were made available at very discounted rates, and they saved many lives during a dangerous phase of the war. With Interceptor production largely phased out in favor of the new Siren, the Canberra's weapons have become expensive to operate, and the Protubérance gunship has come to dominate what remains of the 'civilian-grade escort' niche. Even so, they are the smallest and cheapest Terran vessel with a hangar, and in secure systems where self-defense is less of a concern, surviving units have been adapted for a wide range of uses.<br/><br/>The Canberra's reliance on missile weapons also makes it an uncommon pirate vessel. It is considered a Class C combatant when its missile stations are loaded, and a Class F combatant when they are not."
917, "(fr)TM Florence"
918, "(fr)The Florence is a medical ship with an unusual history. When the virus now known as the Lucerta plague first broke out in Regulus, the local government responded with its usual ineffectual slowness. Instead, representatives of the Regulus Syndicate criminal organization stepped forward, breaking out four mothballed Conestoga-class explorer ships from the Syndicate's vaults and offering them as makeshift hospitals. A strange period of doctors and crime bosses, engineers and gangsters collaborating to keep these impromptu hospitals functional followed, and the end result was effective quarantine of the plague and emergence of the Florence as a distinct class of ship. Modern Florences are an odd mix of converted Conestogas and purpose-built ships, but they all share a common design and shared goal of getting medical assistance where it's needed, when it's needed. The GTA medical corps has recently unveiled an 'official' successor of the Florence in the GTM Hippocrates, but rollout has been slow, and in the mean time, the Florence isn't going anywhere.<br/><br/>As a retrofit to an already outdated design, the Florence is a Class E combatant, and even then barely. A quirk of GTA regulations means the Regulus Syndicate is officially credited as the class's designer, which is something of a sore point given its popularity."
10561, "(fr)The Rakhsh 'recovery ship' is an unusual design, consisting of a versatile docking arm, oversized engines, back-to-back jump drives, and little else. Its purpose is to jump to a ship in distress, secure a docking connection, and jump clear before coming into distress itself. To this end, the Rakhsh's twin jump drives are set up such that the cooldown phase of the primary drive helps jump-start the larger second drive, giving the Rakhsh a very rapid cycle time. Dynamic Metamer introduced the design to mitigate pirate threats in uncontrolled systems and turn around its failing stock price, and has already received several orders. A proposal to commission a military variant is working its way through the GTA Admiralty under the provisional designation $quoteGTR Orestes$quote. One potential concern is that the Rakhsh's massive subspace signature makes it, and any disabled ship it's carrying, very easy to track."
10562, "(fr)Pad"
10563, "(fr)Dock Tunnel"
10564, "(fr)Arm"
919, "(fr)TI Polaris Extension"
920, "(fr)The Polaris modular pylon system is a common drydock seen throughout Terran space. In theory, a network of Polaris pylons can be assembled, modified, and broken down as needed. In practice, interoperability between Polaris modules is temperamental, and once a network is assembled, it's typically left in place to avoid the hassle. Leasing out Polarises to other manufacturers propelled Dynamic Metamer into a commanding position in the galactic economy, but the expense of operating the system has drawn considerable scrutiny in the post-Sol austerity era."
921, "(fr)TI Polaris Pylon"
10565, "(fr)This massive mining hub blurs the line between starship and installation. It is subspace-capable, but extremely slow, with a drive warmup time measured in hours. STX moves the facility only rarely, when too many of the economically useful asteroids in its vicinity have been exploited for it to remain profitable. The facility includes manipulator arms and mountings for asteroid-cracker explosives, and can process many of the more common mineral types by itself, while others are sent off to STX's Namid-class ore processor for further refinement."
