10657, "(fr)Locuste"
1121, "(fr)The Ballista is a successor to the Phoenix V long-range missile. Traditionally, LRMs were fielded by interceptor squadrons, but tactical innovations during the Shivan Incursion have lead to them being more commonly seen on assault fighters, whose large ordnance bays make for a powerful standoff threat. The Ballista is the first LRM to drop support for the aging Valkyrie, allowing the design to push far beyond its original limitations. The Ballista has an effective range of 2800 meters, a kilometer greater than the Phoenix V, with next-gen guidance systems to effectively track targets even in the face of enemy EWAR.<br/><br/>While the Ballista represents official acceptance of the $quotelong-range missile boat$quote tactics developed in the Shivan Incursion, the Alliance has not moved away from traditional interceptor tactics. Proposals for a next-generation interceptor to replace the aging Valkyrie are being fielded, with support for the Ballista as a key requirement. The Ballista is, surprisingly, compatible with the Loki reconnaissance fighter, which can carry a pair of them in specialized external racks, although this equipment is limited to special operations squadrons. A successor to the Ballista is already in development, which is expected to double its already impressive range."
1120, "(fr)Anti-Bomber Missile, Long Range, Slow Target Lock"
1118, "(fr)Ballista"
1117, "(fr)The Phoenix V is the latest iteration of the Phoenix anti-bomber missile. Developed during the Great War, the Phoenix V carries an oversized warhead and powerful main thruster, giving it considerable killing power at a range of just under two kilometers. The Phoenix V is typically employed as an anti-bomber weapon and lacks the maneuverability to track targets effectively in a dogfight.<br/><br/>The Phoenix is often carried by Valkyrie interceptors. This is uniquely problematic given the Valkyrie's aging launch bays, which necessitated several adjustments to the Phoenix V in order to retain compatibility. During the Shivan Incursion, Phoenix missiles mounted on assault fighters proved to be a surprisingly effective combination, and some bomber squadrons later adopted the missile to snipe screening fighters. These factors may precipitate a doctrinal shift in how long-range missiles are deployed, and the requirement for Valkyrie compatibility may be dropped from future iterations of the weapon."
