10636, "(fr)The Lancet is a an anti-subsystem and anti-shield gun fielded by the paramilitary Second Dawn Society. The Lancet fills a similar tactical niche as the Disruptor, but its operating principles are entirely different. The Lancet fires a stream of electrically conductive plasma, destructively linking impacted shields with the firing ship's reactor. This design has also proven highly effective against fighter shields, granting a degree of tactical flexibility. The Lancet's main feature, however, is an array of electromagnetic guidance rings at the weapon's muzzle. These rings coordinate with the firing ship's targeting computer to direct the plasma stream as it exits the barrel. This $quoteaim assist$quote function allows the Lancet to effectively disable small craft with relative ease.<br/><br/>While effective in the hands of a trained pilot, the Lancet suffers from an exorbitant per-unit cost, as well as a number of technical issues. Sustained fire can overwhelm the mechanical tolerances of the aim assist system, leading to a failure mode which the weapon's designer describes as $quotefiring wildly in random directions$quote. When approached by LNA weapons researchers, this same engineer indicated that they'd $quotecompletely given up on solving that$quote, and that $quoteunless you know of a lubricant that can survive a plasma storm and costs less than a cruiser per liter, I'm done with that thing$quote. This attitude is not shared by the larger Second Dawn Society, however$semicolon given the organization's belief in an inevitable second Great War, the utility the weapon would offer in capture operations against Shivan targets compels the organization to continue their research.<br/><br/>While the technical challenges of aim assist are well-known, building the technology into a subsystem disruptor is a creative solution to some of them. Firing the weapon in short bursts is often enough to destroy a subsystem or pierce a shield quadrant without triggering the $quotewild firing$quote issue, and pilots carrying the Lancet are advised to adopt such a firing pattern as a matter of habit. The SDA' stockpile of Lancets is vanishingly small, and they are loathe to part with them, so they may only be loaded out with the authorization of a squadron leader."
10635, "(fr)Tactical Disruptor and shield-breaker,
Experimental aim assist,
Fire in short bursts"
