10823, "(fr)Standard issue flight suit for emergency operation outside of a spacecraft. Shandong Industrial has a near-monopoly on these suits owing to an exclusive contract to produce them for the Alliance."
10824, "(fr)Environmental suit for operation outside of a spacecraft. Often outfitted with specialized tools for mining or construction tasks. These suits' thruster governors are occasionally removed for racing purposes, a practice which is, controversially, fully legal in the Regulus system."
10825, "(fr)The Fourteen Years War and the Great War made abundantly clear the importance of controlling jump nodes, and mine and minesweeping technology developed in parallel. Even today, the Antarès Federation and the Hammer of Light use mines to secure the nodes leading into their systems. The Carillon is an ADEIS mine, drawing on years of wartime expertise combined with the AI's own ingenuity. Typically, Carillons are seeded at important areas like standard mines. During the Lavoisier's ill-fated expedition to Laramis, however, an alternate configuration of the Carillon was encountered, which sacrificed explosive yield for a high-precision jump drive, allowing it to strike like a torpedo from subspace. Fortunately, this weapon seems to require an ADEIS vessel on station to provide coordinates, which can be jammed by readily available electronics warfare options. Until the ADEIS threat is resolved, standing orders are for all Allied convoys throughout Luyten to include at least one ship carrying such a jammer."
10826, "(fr)IN.E.D.A.M.01 is the heart of the ADEIS fleet. It is a fully capable, fully automated command carrier, in flagrant violation of the Third Convention on Autonomous Weapon Systems. The carrier is ADEIS's original design, built around the AI core and vastly augmenting its capabilities. Primary killing power is provided by an unknown number of turreted gauss cannons, supplemented by the same fragmentation turrets carried by the Marie-Morgane gunship. Far more concerning, however, is the ADEIS air wing, which is produced aboard IN.E.D.A.M.01 itself from materials pillaged from other vessels. It is currently believed that the carrier is capable of producing every strikecraft utilized by the ADEIS fleet, including the unique Ddraig and Armorica, which blur the line between strikecraft and torpedo - although the question of where the larger Marie-Morgane and Ker-Ahes are produced remains open.<br/><br/>An additional area of concern centers on IN.E.D.A.M.01's operational capabilities. Conventional Fleet doctrine would call for indirect engagement, attacking IN.E.D.A.M.01's logistical support and surgically destroying key systems in asymmetric warfare. However, strategic analysis suggests that the ship can sustain itself off of material recovered from engagement sites, and has the ability to repair itself without external support$semicolon it is speculated that it carries a complement of utility drones similar to those encountered aboard the ICv Gallécie. ADEIS's ability to field new drone classes suggests that IN.E.D.A.M.01 is capable of modifying its own drone bay$semicolon the ability to upgrade other ship systems is considered likely.<br/><br/>IN.E.D.A.M.01 is a Class S combatant, on par with the Shivan flagship Lucifer."
10827, "(fr)The Ker-Ahes is an ADEIS command-and-control ship with a highly unusual design. First encountered engaging a Hammer of Light formation, it was initially mistaken for a unique ship, and assumed to hold the 'raiders' command staff aboard. It was not until Captain Varner's testimony about the ADEIS project that the true nature of the Ker-Ahes was revealed. A fully autonomous electronics warfare platform, the Ker-Ahes can disrupt Allied targeting, communications, and navigational systems, and provide command-and-control capabilities to support nearby drones. Its most dangerous capability, however, is its oversight of Dahut stealth drones, which cannot operate without an attendant Ker-Ahes, but which are a lethal threat to Allied strikecraft while properly controlled.<br/><br/>Typically, the Ker-Ahes would be considered a Class F combatant. Given its unconventional capabilities and the frequent presence of Dahuts, it has instead been designated a Class A combatant. Fortunately, the ship's 'fins' are easily destroyed by weapons fire, limiting its effectiveness somewhat."
10828, "(fr)With a turret-to-capacity ratio exceeding the PVFr Satis, the Marie-Morgane blurs the line between transport and gunship. Our encounters with this class have shown that these ships are capable of capturing spacecraft, cargo, and debris, and every Marie-Morgane has a central cargo hold with an access door on the top side for this purpose. Marie-Morgane units have been observed loading more material than should fit inside their internal volume, and it's speculated that the Marie-Morgane has some capacity to process scrap onboard.<br/><br/>The Marie-Morgane mounts four frontal coilgun turrets, as well as two 'fragmentation' turrets. These latter weapons use a magnetic sabot to propel a delayed-detonation directional-fragment grenade, filling a niche similar to Allied flak systems, but with increased effectiveness against warship targets.<br/><br/>The Marie-Morgane is a Class B combatant, and pilots attacking them are advised to take advantage of a gap in turret coverage around the Morgen's aft section. In attack roles, they often deploy in pairs, but individual Marie-Morgane are often encountered as well."
10829, "(fr)The Spriggan is a utility drone deployed by IN.E.D.A.M.01 to rapidly onboard salvage. These minimalist support craft are typically seen in large swarms, bringing their mothership raw material from asteroids and the wreckage of broken-up or destroyed ships and stations. Spriggans have almost no advanced systems to them, barring what appears to be an integrated fiberglass hull and retrofitted engines of significant power, capable of quickly shuttling back and forth between a source of raw materials and ADEIS itself.<br/><br/>As an unarmed support vessel, the Spriggan is a Class F combatant. Because of their extreme value to the ADEIS carrier, however, their destruction as targets of opportunity is encouraged."
10830, "(fr)The Gradlon is a highly dangerous but relatively fragile strike bomber. Armed with four coilguns, two turrets, and deep ordnance bays, and equipped with thrust-vectored afterburners comparable to the PVF Horus, the Gradlon carries firepower rivaling the dreaded Shivan Seraphim bomber in a spaceframe scarcely more robust than a TSC 2 cargo container. Gradlons make little effort to evade pursuing fighters, often ignoring them until they have expended their ordinance, but its turret screen more than compensates, especially in formations of four or more. Some pilots have likened it to a down-scaled version of the IGs Marie-Morgane - powerful, but relying entirely on active defenses.<br/><br/>The Gradlon's first appearance ended with the destruction of Wayfarer Station, degrading both logistics and morale across the system. It is considered a Class A threat, and demands a prompt response."
10831, "(fr)The Ys (pronounced 'eess') is an ADEIS bomber first encountered during a strike mission against a major scrapyard, where a wing of them destroyed the GTC Eudore. The Ys occupies a niche somewhere between the Terran Zeus and Medusa, carrying heavy ordnance but being maneuverable enough to have a chance of defending itself. Primary killing power is provided by a heavy version of ADEIS's gauss cannon, which the Ys is capable of employing at extreme range, although it does carry traditional bombs as well. The Ys seems specifically designed to frustrate conventional interceptor tactics, laying down long-ranged fire to draw escort fighters away from their charges' point defense screens. Ys sometimes carry shield-breaker missiles to soften up defending fighters for their escorts.<br/><br/>Given its unusual weapons suite, the Ys is considered a Class B threat."
10832, "(fr)With the possible exception of the Dahut stealth fighter, the Korrigan fighter is the most advanced of ADEIS's fighter drones. It is competent in a range of roles, which it achieves largely by virtue of packing many highly optimized systems on its large frame, although it is most commonly employed for fighter suppression. The Korrigan's armor and shielding approach GTA heavy fighter standards, while its maneuvering thruster suite is comparable to Allied superiority fighters. Offensively, the Korrigan carries the standard suite of ADEIS projectile weaponry, as well as anti-shield missiles.<br/><br/>The Korrigan's arrival into Luyten conflict was abrupt and unexpected. Korrigans were first encountered escorting IN.E.D.A.M.01 in the Doceitov Cloud, and were soon encountered at engagement sites throughout the system. It is possible that ADEIS specifically developed them to shore up the Ankou's limitations engaging Allied fighters in realspace.<br/><br/>Korrigan fighters are a Class A combatant, and should be engaged with caution."
10833, "(fr)The Dahut is an ADEIS stealth drone. Dahuts appear very stripped down compared to similar classes, lacking shields, adequate maneuvering thrusters, or even an onboard AI. They have only been seen escorting Ker-Ahes AWACS units, which seem to control them remotely. We believe these are intentional tradeoffs to enable the Dahut's stealth capabilities.<br/><br/>Previous experiments into stealth fighters have mostly focused on 'passive' systems, such as those carried by the GTF Loki. So-called 'active' stealth, wherein a spacecraft blends into surrounding space, have historically been regarded as highly impractical. Dahuts have two distinct advantages over conventional spacecraft in this area. Firstly, the Ker-Ahes' electronics warfare systems provide an environment that is easier to blend into than normal space. Secondly, delegating control functions to the AWACS frees up internal volume and power for the stealth systems. How ADEIS devised such a system is a topic of ongoing discussion among LNA researchers.<br/><br/>Dahuts are fragile and poorly maneuverable, but their weapons pack considerable punch. Their magnetic projectile 'shotguns' are not only effective anti-hull weapons, but have a disruptive effect on their targets' electronics as well. A Ker-Ahes controlling a Dahut wing should be regarded as a Class A combatant, while the Dahuts themselves should be treated as Class B combatants. While uncontrolled Dahuts are helpless, they have occasionally been seen making unassisted jumps. Their destruction is therefore encouraged barring orders to the contrary."
10834, "(fr)The Iseut drone defies standard classifications. Tentatively classified as an $quoteinterphasic raider,$quote the Iseut acts as an independent hunter-killer, able to effectively engage ships both in subspace and in realspace. Typical tactics include an opening salvo of shield-breaker missiles, after which the ship engages with its four burst-fire railguns. Iseuts have primarily been observed near subspace nodes, and occasionally act as escort for Marie-Morgane-class capture craft.<br/><br/>The Iseut mounts only a diminutive shield generator, and gains much of its protection from iridium-molybdenum armor plating. In realspace, the Iseut maintains a maneuverability rating between the Hercules and the Apollo, but its subspace capabilities are far more concerning. The Iseut integrates SUTRAC equipment into its navigational system and is capable of pursuing ships attempting to flee into subspace.<br/><br/>The Iseut it is a Class A combatant in subspace. In realspace, its weapons suite still earns it Class B classification."
10835, "(fr)The Ankou appears to be ADEIS's basic space superiority drone. As with all known ADEIS ships, the Ankou lacks a pilot. Internal volumes that would be occupied with life support seem to be used for propulsion instead. This makes the Ankou swift and maneuverable for its size.<br/><br/>Like the smaller Camma, the Ankou's weaponry is munition-based. Scans indicate that the ship typically carries two hull-attack coilguns and a variant specialized in destroying subsystems. The Ankou possesses no secondary banks or shields. Bizarrely, no chaff or flare launchers have been detected. The Ankou relies exclusively on its small target profile and exceptional maneuverability for defense. The Ankou's flight characteristics have been compared to the dreaded Shivan Dragon class.<br/><br/>The Ankou is considered a Class C combatant. With their onboard disruptor weaponry, Ankou wings are often employed in capture operations."
10836, "(fr)The IF Camma is small drone typically employed as a scout or swarm combatant. Offensive function is restricted to two burst-fire railguns apparently derived from the GTW-65 Railgun. No secondary banks or shields are evident. Like the GTW-65, Camma guns are significantly more effective against unshielded targets, or fighters with a breached shield quadrant. Adjust tactics accordingly.<br/><br/>Camma debris is highly heterogeneous. Analysis suggests that Cammas are accreted together from material surplus. Disturbingly, serial numbers from missing transports, shuttles, and fighters have been found in Camma debris.<br/><br/>The Camma is considered a Class C threat to transports and unsupported warships, and a Class D threat otherwise. In spite of its low classification, all personnel are expected to be vigilant. ADEIS ships exhibit exceptional subspace agility, and a single Camma rarely remains that way for long."
10837, "(fr)A preeminent tourist attraction in Adhara, the Kirstenbosch Sky Gardens were built shortly after initial colonization of the system by a group of Terran entrepreneurs seeking to draw visitors to the system. Despite construction taking a significant period of time, the Sky Gardens have been a popular tourist attraction for decades, rated by the Galactic Terran Board of Travel as one of the top ten most regularly visited attractions in all of known space. After the collapse of the Sol jump node and the loss of connection with their original owner, the Sky Gardens were rechristened as the Summerland Resort. Notable attractions within the station include the Root Tunnels, made from hydroponically grown trees which can support the weight of a whole family, and the Abkhazian Zoo of the Exotic, the first Terran zoo to ever host Vasudan wildlife, including rare living examples of the critically endangered Apsu-Hek."
10838, "(fr)The Hégéia is a next-gen construction and repair drone, introduced by the Gulisano Precision Group to compete with the Phidias. Designed with an advanced neural-net AI and the latest in repair systems, the Hégéia is intended for premium consumers seeking to decrease turnaround times on ship maintenance. STX Exploration helped bankroll the Hégéia' development, citing a desire to ease maintenance of their mobile mining hub in Luyten, drawing the attention of several construction firms and system governments."
10839, "(fr)Like its smaller cousin the Magellan, the Elcano is an old explorer ship given new life in the spaceborne society of Luyten. Where the Magellan fills the role of a mobile office block, often tasked with a specific research task or administrative function, the Elcano is a primary habitat for up to eleven thousand citizens. The Luyten New Alliance maintains three of these ships, one near - and named after - each of the system's three jump nodes. At full capacity, these ships would host populations to rival Amanu Station. In practice, these ships are still sparsely populated, providing the LNA with considerable capacity for immigration.<br/><br/>While Elcanos have very thick hulls, they are utterly defenseless on their own. LNA Elcanos rely on attendant Dainsleif platforms and fighter support from Amanu Station for protection. Standing orders are for these ships to jump to a defensible location at the first sign of hostile activity, but this protocol has yet to be tested in action. The separation between thousands of Luyten citizens and certain death may be as small as a single bomber pass."
10840, "(fr)Paramilitary strike bomber. Limited ordnance, but highly survivable."
10841, "(fr)The Pélé is a rare class of fighter designed and constructed by the paramilitary Second Dawn Society. While such heavy ordnance in civilian hands would be highly illegal in Galactic Terran space, the Pélé was officially greenlit by the Luyten New Alliance in exchange for SDA cooperation in policing the system's Oort Cloud.<br/><br/>The Pélé is built for endurance, and frequently deployed in pairs on long patrols. The ship is powerful, but notoriously finicky, and Pélé crews are held in high regard aboard Megiddo Station. The Pélé mounts a special railgun in one of its three gun banks, believed to be derived from technology developed by the GTI's Hades Rebellion."
10842, "(fr)Paramilitary gunship. High endurance. Three gun mounts."
10843, "(fr)Mining patrol ship repurposed as scout fighter."
10844, "(fr)Obsolete assault fighter, exceedingly durable but unmaneuverable."
10845, "(fr)Obsolete heavy fighter. Capable of threatening civilian ships but not useful against modern vessels."
